GDkfCfTlOu_jqOyEEeu0mA.text: Their gluten-free vegan doughnut was out of this world good. However they have no decaf coffee options even for an Americano which sucks for me because I can't drink caffeinated coffee, so that is the only reason I took a star off and it would've only been a half star if that was possible. 2xUgbLA_s05Eyo_uDKim1w.text: Why oh why can't we have a Nami in San Diego. Sigh.  I make sure to stop by every time I am in town. Although other places attempt vegan desserts, only Nami really nails it. Be sure to try the Sunday brunch! The Benedict Arnold will have you craving more.  Today I tried the Tsoft serve and it is just as delicious as I imagined it. Their donuts, cupcakes, and cake are the best vegan treats I have had...and I have tried my fair share of vegan desserts!  Great job, Nami. Now all you need to do is open a location in SD.

bUV8lYdxXD3gSO8qlX4qTw.text: Delicious treats, desserts, smoothies, coffees, and food! PLEASE OPEN A NAMI IN TUCSON!!!!!!

HtxoqsRcYH3AqgOIY6M8Dg.text: Protip - getting a fruit tsoynami with chocolate chip is a great life choice. Right next to Green, Nami has a diverse array of vegan desserts. They're definitely a little over sweet, but if you keep your sweet tooth in tow then you're in for a treat.   Just a note that there isn't always a lot of space to sit.

yD4B2z06Vrq9Faj7Z2pNBQ.text: Went for the first time on Saturday, the ice cream is delicious!! I got the dough boy and my husband the pb and chocolate...it was amazing. Will be back soon!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Yum

Enj0RJsVEMSyS7tsUEBEOw.text: In my searching of vegan options in Phoenix I stumbled across Nami that was listed as a 100% vegan ice cream shop/bakery/coffee shop.  Further search brought up photos of indulgent ice cream sundaes called tSoynamis.  We had the perfect opportunity to check out Nami following my birthday dinner at Pizza Heaven Bistro, since it was just up the street.  Not only does is Nami 100% vegan but they also carry many gluten-free options for those interested. Nami is located just next door to it's restaurant counterpart, Green.  The staff was super friendly.  Given so many choices they also gave us a hand selecting our tSoynami.  My husband went with the "Mash" which is a mash up of baked goods and other yummy additions of the maker's choice.   In other words a "Mash" will never be the same.  He was quite impressed by the tastiness of his treat and I will admit I stole many spoonfuls of his.  I chose the "Fluffernutterin'" which contained organic peanut butter, banana, ricemellow fluff and toasted marshmallow flavor.  Definitely a win in my book.  What made our experience even better?  When I saw that our treats were served in a biodegradable 16oz cup along with a wooden biodegradable spoon.  I'm all about reducing my carbon footprint.  Checking out their Facebook page I see that they have Hot Fudge Sundays and Sunday Brunch, both of which I know I will have to check out.  Not to mention, I definitely need to try some of their vegan baked goods ASAP. Vegan donuts exist too!!  The good and bad is that it's a pretty big trek to Nami for us.  Good since I think I'd be there every day.  Bad, that I wish it wasn't that far.  Even so I've  visited Nami 4 times since arriving in Phoenix just under a month ago -_-.  My excuses are that once it was my birthday and the other 3 I just happened to be in the area while exploring all Phoenix has to offer.  Hey, I had to take advantage of my opportunities.  Yes, vegan soft serve ice cream exists and it truly is heavenly.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Flutternutterin&#39;
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. View from the street
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Love the wooden spoons

fw2usKGcyNPr_hrkKxL3zw.text: I scream, you scream, we all scream for. . . Soynamis! So it doesn't quiet have the same ring as "ice cream" but it's still delicious! And you don't feel as weighed down/guilty after finishing a Soynami as you do when you polish of a DQ Blizzard.  The first time I went I had the Almond Oy Vey!, which was good, but not amazing.   Then a friend recommended the Coffee Coco Loco with the addition of Peanut Butter, and it's so good that I can't bring myself to try anything else. If you remotely like coffee and/or PB you will love it! I've never tried any of the baked goods, but I did bring home a chocolate cupcake for my boyfriend one night. He said it was really good (evidenced by the fact that I wasn't offered a bite), but the icing was overly sweet.   I shouldn't have written this review... now I'm really craving some Nami!

EDKm6kIiJLwRQhTDqcYxvQ.text: The Vegan ice cream is soo delicious!!!  They have such interesting flavor combinations.  I'm not even vegan but I loved the ice cream so much I had to come back before I left town!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. S&#39;mores soynami and espresso

CtsGg7PkrRDFZpnmACuVBg.text: Came here a while back with a friend and it was definitely worth the drive! Parking  was a bit tight since it's a pretty small place. I can't remember the exact flavor of my tsoynami, something with bananas, but it was so, so good. I also got a quiche to go and that was delicious as well. I'll definitely be back!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. tsoynami!

h8RMKf5PqwkIRD19PdeYqw.text: For not being a dessert guy and a huge meat guy (could never understand this veggie vegan thing) Nami had some darn good desserts that weren't over sweet and had flavors that I don't normally taste in desserts.  Had a coffee and the donuts (vegan ones at that) and the fiance ordered some chocolate cookie.  Actually for something very simply prepared the taste was really good.  The coffee tasted spot on with a good balance of bitterness and smoothness (put 2 sugars and just a splash of what I assume was cream)  So if your vegetarian or want a dessert that doesn't overload you with processed sugars, hydrogenated oils and other crap that is in most bulk desserts, check this place out.

Ib7MOoNMctHYWDB8bzENEg.text: I love the food here and it's pretty much one of 3 vegan/vegetarian spots in Phoenix but the service is UNBELIEVABLY slow. I don't even walk in the door if there is a line. Even with no line it took about 20 minutes to get an acai bowl on a Wednesday at 10:40am. Don't ever come here if you're in a hurry, but it's a lovely place to sit and chat a whole morning away with a friend.

tIEhMkrwajbWtIiqVKuZrA.text: Great spot to hit for vegan pastries and delicious drinks. I've had and loved their "Betterfinger" tsoynami. It's basically a vegan version of a mcflurry for those who were allowed to eat those as a kid....but way better. It's vegan soft serve with mashed up chocosticks, chocolate chips and some sort of toffee syrup.   Also delicious is their "yanky-doodle" cookie. It's two chewy soft perfect snickerdoodle cookies with some sort of sweet vegan cream between like a cream sandwich. Holy yum.   Their donuts are a bit cake like and not really donutty like the gf donuts at Jewel's bakery. But this should not stop you because hey, cake rocks too!   Other notables... A mint latte drink, vegan chocolate shake (not too sweet and really great), cupcakes etc.  There is seating but it's not very comfy cozy...a bit more on the modern industrial meets cement and wood. You'll get over it though as you delight in sugar.  All in all, this place should definitely be a part of your life.

C71BoH7g6PR0KBcHqVSkfw.text: My favorite sweet spot! I love the banana cream pie ice "cream" and for my lady, the seasonal pumpkin pie

-4rN2jtNETXhyYHcsDUmaQ.text: Always a line out the door for Nami. The food is incredible! Try the vegan Huevos Rancheros burrito. So filling and fantastically yummy!   Knocked one star off because of the unfriendly girl @ the counter. She barely smiled and looked highly annoyed. The rest of the staff is extremely pleasant!   Still love the food though and will keep coming back!

IhyjW-3OJorQAPW9s1pUPg.text: A bit of a trek from where we were, but props to this store for being open on labor day weekend. The venue's a little small, the staff a little harried despite the lack of a line and the limited menu items. Despite the wait, we managed to obtain one of each of the cupcakes to try - a little dry, but they were tasty enough that i couldn't believe they were vegan! Would come again if it was closer and/or the wait wasn't so long.

1F6mizkswiBgpqejtXJEsw.text: Amazing vegan desserts! I tried the pumpkin spice cake. The frosting was the best I've ever had- vegan or non! The cake was super moist. The soft serve was amazing as well.

3nm1K6vp9oxGCz09K8E8uQ.text: The only thing I EVER get at Nami is their Soynami.  I don't like or eat vegan food, and I think it's blasphemous to have vegan cupcakes sitting on their counter, but whatever -- to each his own.  But the Soynami is delish!  You get the benefit of a whole cup of soft serve without feeling heavy afterwards.  I always get the vanilla with fresh fruit (bananas, peaches, strawberries and mangos).  Sooooo good, especially on a hot day!

0VeitdCGa2JgUrhwWEb0QQ.text: Had to write an update since they now serve brunch on Sundays.  I went in and was slightly disappointed to see that just about everything was with tofu scramble (not the hugest tofu fan), but I made a selection: The Benedict Arnold.  Made up of roasted asparagus, Canadian "bacon", "hollandaise", and scrambled tofu.  You can get it in a bowl (for the gluten-free kids), or wrapped in a tortilla.  I chose the tortilla, cause well...I love a damn good burrito!    It came out, and I was ready.  First bite in, and I knew we had a winner!  The combination of all flavors was perfection to my taste buds.  They have a decent selection to choose from, including: cinnamon rolls, yogurt parfaits, other burrito or bowl delights, coffees and juices, and more.  It was a nice brunch experience and hope to come back for more.

7j6_MqATdja4rt-5EqzUSg.text: The vegan blueberry doughnut might be the best doughnut I've ever had. It was so soft and flavorful! Not only did it have blueberries scattered throughout, it also tasted like graham crackers, which I loved. I only meant to try a couple bites, but I ended up eating the whole thing.  I also tried their soy ice cream with animal crackers mixed in. It's icier than regular ice cream, but letting it melt a bit helps. The addition of the mix-ins turned it into a vegan, customizable McFlurry!  If I lived in Phoenix, I'd definitely be a regular here.

6a6LLtDv2KDaOO3uMDBn_w.text: Man!  The ice cream here is better than real ice cream!  Get the chocolate mint ice cream.  So amazing!  And affordable!

-aitXFiF4Vv1kBuE6kVNsw.text: Mmmmmmmm, need I say more?  You had  The Hubs at "vegan blizzard" and did not disappoint.

JL2_kOb6cWJ9FraKRTprcQ.text: The ice cream is great, even though they have somehow defied logic and left out all dairy items. Bravo. I'll be back to this cool neighborhood spot.

8j0QQQoBDOKi_oSlivBSzA.text: Super fantastic vegan deserts and coffee! Handmade ice cream!  Donuts! Cupcakes!  Wow, so awesome!!!  Really a great place. And if you want food, go next door to Greens (restaurant owned by same people). Thank you so much for making my tummy happy :o)

ich7cJcw-GtC7NckaUCU2g.text: Just had their Gluten Free raspberry donut and again I am so impressed. Before eating gf donuts were my go to feel good food. I have tried assorted bakery and boxed types to no avail. This donut was moist, not dry or gritty like others. The flavor was exceptional and the frosting on top made it the absolute best GF Donut I have had to date.

bIb3O1eWdxhtCMYT75Fpug.text: Prickly pear iced tea, I REPEAT TRY THE PRICKLY PEAR ICED TEA. RIGHT. NOW. The chai tea blew my mind, might have surpassed Lux's (just might have). Tried an apple fritter ball and went to heaven! Okay on a serious note, this is a cute little vegan coffee shop that provides vegan pastries, ice cream (yes to my lactose intolerant friends!), and food. The shop is cute, the two girls that were running the show behind the counter were kickin butt and takin names since they were slammed and they were super helpful to us Nami virgins (my husband and I). We will definitely be back to try the ice cream because we kept on drooling seeing all the people walk by with these amazing looking cups nestled in their hands. OH JYAHHHH.....

_bmpXEm44MrYGUHDs5JxqA.text: After stuffing ourselves at Green, my husband and I walked over to Nami to top off our meal. We each ordered a Tsoynami. I had the Cookies 'n' Cream and my husband had Coffee Coco Loco.   The Tsoynamis where huge but they were so good and not overly rich like whole milk ice cream. The added ingredients were plentiful and I had cookie pieces and chocolate syrup in every bite. The wooden spoons wigged us out a little, but we worked through it.  After sitting in Nami eating our Tsoynamis, we couldn't resist getting a few items to go. My husband was excited to find Ethiopian whole coffee beans at a great price ($10). I got a Nami cake--a chocolate cupcake reminiscent of the traditional Hostess variety with white cream filling and chocolate frosting. My first vegan cupcake and such a great one to start with. We also got a delicious looking oatmeal cream pie cookie that was equally delicious. There were so many cupcakes and delicious baked goods to choose from, it was hard to decide. I think Nami will become a regular stop every time we go to Green.

u2AQyUx69WiysfYNo8Y_HA.text: Very fun place!  Vegan ice cream is such a novel idea, and they do it well.  I had the chai tiramisu tSoynami and my sister had the almond oy vey.  It was my birthday, so she let me swap with her because I liked hers a lot better!

ZUSnuLWZ8DcJuvdgPtzI2g.text: Holy yumminess!!!! Ok so I'm a meat eater, but prefer my veggies and this place would totally turn me into a vegan if I only knew how to make their dishes. We have been frequenting this place for Sunday brunch and working our way to sample the entire menu. My absolute fave is the sage sausage  hash as you can't even tell it's vegan and it is perfectly seasoned. Make sure you save room for the tsoynami. Thank you for this delicious cafe & bakery because I will be here EVERY week!

g-uIrqVYMmIAXUxCwvBdsg.text: Yummy! Everything is so good!! My fav is the Betterfinger Tsoynami!!

I felt refreshed after finishing the Dough Boy, which after eating non-vegan ice cream I wouldn't have. You can't even tell it's not ice cream except that it is more icy than milk and doesn't have the gross aftertaste. Drooling thinking of it right now...

63u-kV0n3P2D1fQT0pPwLw.text: tsoynamis (which you an get at both green locations too) are delicious!  my boyfriend thoroughly devoured all the other goodies we got with me barely getting a taste - but they were pretty good! especially the butterscotch marshmallow squares.  they also make donuts on weds and sunday - i wish we could have tried them!

T015IFIAs62xevbCpzH41g.text: All I can say is this coffee/ice cream/sweet shop is inspirational!  Coupled with it's parent restaurant in the same parking lot, you are certainly in for a great night of eats!  All of my experiences have been nothing short of amazing.  I have eaten at Nami for breakfast, desert after lunch, desert after dinner and for a mid-day snacks.  The coffee is all vegan and fair trade and they offer all kinds of milks to add in with your lattes and such.  Packaging for the coffee is also awesome.  For breakfast, you can opt for some power vegan bars sitting on the counter, quiche or search through the sweets display case.  For deserts, my favorite is the cupcake which was inspired with the Hostess cake but it's vegan!  That's right... chocolaty-goodness with white cream filing and icing on top! oh my!  They also have a chai cupcake which has a cinnamon-like icing on top... yum yum!  They have snicker doodles with icing sandwiched in between and mini-cookies to scarf down.  Everything is vegan!  They are famous for something known as a soy-nami but I've never made it to the vegan ice cream!  I'm always opting for the aforementioned sweets!  If I ever get to one, I will review again... They also do sundaes and live music on Sunday nights.  For dinner, walk across the parking lot to Green Pastures.  See my review for this restaurant as well.

5YXlN6WqQKGbp_QXAvrIRQ.text: There was more foam (an inch deep) then coffee in my small cactus haboob. The Nami Mcbagel sandwich was alright, all I could taste is the spicy part of the salsa. Honestly I was very disappointed with the service as well, they forgot my friends plain bagel... It was the first thing we order. The fruit was delicious though!

BD9gzWq0LrRMf_xlgI6kjQ.text: Oh nami why? I have a sweet tooth and this place definitely satisfies it. My favorite is the cookie dough tsoynami. It doesn't taste vegan but is. Definitely worth a stop if you're in the area.

It's a cute little place too. Great for hanging out. The people behind the counter are really sweet as well.

KRSGUuaCs6wMlLIN0rdjhQ.text: I picked up some maple brown sugar donuts, a slice of cookie dough cake, an oatmeal cookie w/ frosting inside and some cupcakes (carrot cake, red velvet, etc.) today to celebrate a special occasion. Each of the treats was rich with flavor, moist and totally decadent! I will be back to try their breakfast and coffee items!

v1BMXLuxbIs5XX_eLsIZaA.text: Had the banana cream pie "ice cream" and probably the best vegan "ice cream" I've had to date. Smooth, creamy flavor!

LQz9lwLaO7XzPWWKLovo3Q.text: Well, it's always my goal to try something different and that's definitely what Nami was! My boyfriend & I are by no means vegan, however we were in the area and he found this place under desserts on Yelp. We figured we'd stop in to give it a try. Was it good? .. By vegan standards, I think so? Would we return? Debatable.  The biggest problem we had at this place was that we didn't really understand what the menu items were. After a look over their offerings, I wanted just plain soft-serve, so I picked vanilla. Or more like "vanilla" I suppose. More than anything, it tasted super coconut-y. I'm not a fan of the coconut flavoring taste so that was disappointing as was the texture. It was almost just icy and not at all soft like what I'm used to. I did get used to it after a few bites but it almost felt like my teeth were hurting because the dessert was so cold!  My boyfriend was actually looking for a pastry and though the betterfinger would be tasty. A tsoy-nami is definitely not a pasty. It's more like what a concrete is from DQ for the non-vegan folk. I probably would have been better off ordering that since it actually had toppings to mask the flavor of the vanilla soft-serve. He also wasn't a fan of coconut taste but said that he didn't care for the texture more than anything else.  Like previously mentioned, I think by vegan standards, it was alright. Overpriced, however I've never had vegan ice-cream before. I suppose if I couldn't have regular milk, I'd probably come here to get a soy-based treat. The best part was that after eating my whole cup of soft-serve, I didn't feel like I had a sugar overload.  The staff was friendly but not very helpful. We saw a couple of customers there who seemed really annoyed, I'm guessing because they had to wait a while to get everything they had ordered. We didn't have to wait too long to get our order.  If you're in the area, check this place out. I'm interested in trying the vegan restaurant Green, which is right next to it.

_Nr5o4HaVRP15eNOWI_bNg.text: I've been to Nami's twice. The first time I got a donut and it was delicious! It was worth it. The second time I got a Chai Tiramisu tsoynami and I was hugely disappointed. There was barely any chai flavor to it and it was just a big mushy mess.  I'll give them another try but not anytime soon.

z4z0eqxnWsQ0iRtGQn_wOg.text: This place is good for a ice cream with a lot of stuff in it. I'm more of a simple person. My girlfriend on the other hand loves to mix everything up. Parking sucks.

mh5pz3wv4e6NsPfqOllRag.text: Amazing treats - I love their cinnamon roll, cupcakes, and ice cream! I took my family from Oklahoma here and they absolutely LOVED the vegan burritos even though they eat eggs, cheese, and meat. The brunch here is outta this world. I highly recommend the wing ding dang burrito, biscuits and gravy, or whatever the Sunday brunch special is. The chicken and waffles with a bloody maria is my idea of the perfect Sunday brunch!

ogPJWnUjIFOMl3ow_Dgjhg.text: Trying out a tSoynami should be on everyone's bucket list. These DQ Blizzard-style treats will dispel any preconceived notions about vegan food. My favorite tSoynamis are the Dough Boy and the Rocky Road.  Also, they have amazing donuts--you just have to get there early enough to snag one!  If you know any vegan food haters, get them a tSoynami and watch their pessimism quickly turn into brain freeze.  The only reason I'm giving Nami a 4 stars instead of a 5 is because it seems like they are still figuring out their breakfast/brunch situation. The last time I went in for brunch things seemed a little disorganized and the food wasn't as good as their dessert items.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Dough Boy tSoynami ($5) AMAZING!

mVMBA9IaJcPavBq9UcT2xg.text: Delicious vegan food, clean restaurant, great people,  nice place, love sunday specials Yummy chilaquiles, tres leches french toast, biscuits N gravy, the best tsoynamis, this is the only place I eat icecream, love it.

7v-W0rseF5GdFYD7TzOdzA.text: Thank you for having Vegan breakfast in Phoenix. Good food and coffee selection. I do not recommend sitting out back, just a lot of vegetation and not much air flow - leads to bugs. But overall this a GREAT little place and I would recommend it to everyone

zovceUsfHBzwHEX2DZ1niw.text: If you want a creative, delicious, thoughtful, good for the earth meal VISIT NAMI!!! We are frequent visitors (about once a week, usually Sunday brunch) and every visit has been memorable. We have ordered the biscuits and gravy, the big ol burrito, the donuts, the cupcakes, the Benedict as a burrito, and the Rodney Dangerfield. Even with a line out the door service is fast, and friendly!   The restaurant itself is small and intimate. They have indoor and outdoor seating and during brunch seat next door at Green.   The pastry case is always full of delicious, colorful, and (of course) always vegan treats. You won't be able to help yourself but to order one (or 5).  The donuts are dense and sweet and always come in creative flavors that put any other donut (vegan or not) to shame.   You DO NOT HAVE TO BE VEGAN to eat here. I promise that the food you enjoy at Nami is tastier and better for you and your environment than you can get at any other restaurant.

Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Biscuits and Gravy with tofu eggs and potatoes.

_8YNqFpaGFDwOlfYT7eXlA.text: I got the Yodeling Devil dessert. It was a Devil's food cake swirled in with a chocolate and vanilla soft serve ice cream. This concoction was really good. I couldn't believe it was vegan. The only thing that could be improved upon was customer service. The guy who rang us up was like a college stoner guy (nothing wrong with that! Just do it on your own time. Not at work).

YRqZEc6DF6XZmdBX2rwexA.text: This place is one-of-a-kind! Vegan soft serve and treats! I love all their soft serve creations and options, which are numerous, diverse, and fun. More importantly, they all taste very good. You have the option of choosing which soft serve you want: vanilla, chocolate, or swirl.   The place itself is a tiny shop and seating can be limited during busy times. The same idea applies to parking. Customer service is always great. The employees are always friendly, and they always work very quickly.

vJjPHWYyXetzPIMWDPoIRw.text: We came here after years of seeing all of their great treats on social media. We were sorely disappointed when we arrived, and they only had a handful of options to choose from. We ended up with a cookies + cream cupcake and snickerdoodle cookie sandwich. Both were good, and we appreciated that the frosting in the cookie sandwich wasn't overly sweet. Hopefully they'll start sharing their daily offerings on social media so people don't waste time going there to find they are very limited in their options.

jCDaOzMII2KsM-gtSiO8tA.text: Delicious Vegan Desserts!  My husband and I have had multiple tSoynamis and pastry treats here. Our favorites are: the Dough Boy and the PB 'n' J but we have also tried the specials: Banana Cream and Strawberry something and they were so good. The place is small, there's a wait sometimes, and parking is tight but be patient. Your nami will be worth the wait!

GiUf-VMAUwdvq4cx-xRefQ.text: We decided to take a coffee break at this cute little place when we were visiting Phoenix and saw Michael U's review.  We had: espresso shake and pistachio donut. I must admin that I'm a fan of their creations.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Espresso shake
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Pistachio donut

G7GOVmSfFzAiudQQNtLEUQ.text: Love you Nami. A good collection of delicious house made vegan pastries.  And the real reason we always came to Nami....... For the yummy Tsoynami's.  Great list of choices for what you liked. And they are perfect size. Not too small and not too big. Last time i was at Nami they cost $5. But ive been told the price went up a little.  Ive looked and i cannot find any place here in Portland similar to Nami. I even got my meat eating, cow dairy loving friends hooked on the Tsoynami's. They would all finish the whole Tsoynami. Nothing left in the cup. (Lol) thats how darn good they are. And some times would go for a second one.  Great average sized seating area inside and patio seating out front or in the back. We never got over there for breakfast but its some thing i wished i did. I usually went to Nami in the afternoon or at night. If you ever think of branching out. Please come to Oregon Portland to be specific.

3GEdIKeX6Zpgfqyc_3F21w.text: Super good stuff! I just wish the wait wasn't as long as in was for just a frozen yogurt! The layout is very modern and clean but a little small for how much clientele they bring in. I'll be back only because it was so delicious.   I changed my rating to five stars because on my most recent trip this morning. Not only was the food delicious and nutritious. It was an awesome service and all the staff were super fun and engaging even with how busy they were. Keep up the good work!!

V__l3OPwlSWAmTJFCT_SHw.text: Great little place. Staff is very friendly. Owner is a hard worker and attentive. My daughter got the yogurt parfait and she loved it. Will come again.

zMvi9d70IHV44XggFDuJ4w.text: I have converted from vegetarian to veganism since the time of my original review. Now I love Nami even more!  Favourite tsoynamis: PB & J, Banana Cream Pie, Lemonbar (when they have it!) and also the Funny Bunny that was around briefly in the spring.   If you follow them on Facebook or Instagram you can be lured to come in by their yummy photos, which happens to me on a regular basis.   I often meet non-vegan friends here and they've all loved it as well.

1Mk6rmQJFJ17xSbM3tx1Dg.text: I love this place. Always packed when i get there which makes me happy. The banana cream pie soycream is amazing. People who work here are super friendly and polite.Wish theyd have doughnuts more often though. theyre never available when im there. And they need to put prices on their displayed desserts so i dont have to ask how much everything is. Other than that, i love what this place stands for and i will be back again and again!

BGxJXuwcpMf7N_zeWr91jw.text: I'm a regular here every Sunday, if I don't dine in, I take it to go..  But today,  I felt as if I'm a regular there, they don't need to treat me as special anymore and that im always going to go back... Today, my nephew and I ordered the sunday special. It was very delicious by the way, the pancakes was amazing. It had brought to my attention why my nephew and I had to share the syrup bottle, instead of having our own. Which we usually do. It was never a problem before. Then my girlfriend and her fiance showed up, ordered the same thing, and their plate looked better than mine. Not only that they had their own syrup, she had two pancakes and more items on her plate than I did.   I never complain,  i love this place. I talk about this place all the time, tell them to come here allll the time. its not a huge deal, but it was bothering me. Its not like I was going to eat the whole pancake, but it was the portion control that I didn't get. Why should mine be any different? shrugs.. nami is starting to get well known, busier and probably just half ass everything just to get the customer going and what not.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Sunday brunchhhhhh
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

luYHYDIbt35oiYiwSTkJyQ.text: A bit pricey but amazing nonetheless. The toddy is sooo good unsweetened over ice. Everyone that works here is so cute and very sweet - also really nice to my dog, unlike many other coffee shops that tend to glare at you when you come in holding a dog in your arm.   love love love

IHpkyFsQWnfA8D1_W1Pf5Q.text: Baked vegan desserts are great, if a bit on the dense side. Their shakes, which are like their version of a vegan McFlurry are dope! The interior has a cool, punk vibe. The only thing that would make them even better was if they offered a few more savory options for folks who want more than just sweets.

e0reZX689rVTfpYzHH3iyw.text: Grits were excellent - spicy, cheesy (or well cheese-like) hominy chunks rather than instant packet grits. Servings are big for sides as well. I rather create my own meal of sides rather than an entree. As a vegetarian, I went between here and Green next door my whole Phoenix stay.   The only thing that stuck out to me was when I ordered a pour over, before I even finished paying I received it. What? One of the main aspects of a pour over is that it's brewed fresh for you, cup by cup. Instead, I got coffee that was already made from a vat or percolator. It tasted rather watery and flavorless. More akin to diner coffee. Okay, maybe the pour over was pre-made and poured cup by cup into a giant vat. Who knows? That is more time consuming than what it's worth. Just sell drip coffee and call it drip coffee and charge less.

MNze7kzj88p_9OjkPcBo1Q.text: I came here with my girlfriend and we ordered a big size iced mocha only to be disappointed. The cup size itself is very small compared to the price I paid. The cup was also filled with ice which made the quantity of the drink even smaller. Hoping to maybe get a possible refill due to over amount of ice, the employee told me that that was there usual quantity. The drink tasted fine, but for the price it is extremely over priced. It's hard to see myself comeback here.

SElUM-jagRQClrPyZuBT9g.text: I got a little confused because their sign is by a building the same color and on the door of the building it says Nami is next door. Other than that, I really liked the chocolate shake I got. It was very refreshing and not too sweet. A bit of an icey texture, which I liked. There were plenty of drinks I would like to try next, maybe the prickly pear tea or a steamer ( I don't drink coffee). The place was small, but comfortable with a good amount of seating. Lots of young people here. The parking lot was pretty small. Prices are a little above average. I wish the cashier would have bothered to tell me specials and whatnot because I was a bit at a loss of what to order.

WVzoeqSctEa9f5xGBswEpQ.text: Better come here ASAP if you are a Phoenician and vegan. Amazing selections and everything is vegan. All the soft serve soynamis are delicious and you have to try the house made vegan cream for the coffee. Would go every morning if could/lived closer. 5 stars.

WkaRz-Db7GmVabYC54IHRw.text: Yummy Nami! The tSoynami is so delicious here! I've tried quite a few of them, but Don Quixote is my favorite! My fiance who is all about regular ice cream absolutely loves the dough boy tSoynami! I love the coffee & the cup cakes too! You won't be disappointed with whatever you try here. It's a small shop with scarce seating, but they have a few outdoor tables. The parking can be a tight squeeze and limited and the prices here can be pricey, but it's well worth it for a tasty treat!

jC2z73qd8SQonuZxDJOWuw.text: We got a small vegan and gluten free chocolate cake for our small elopement ceremony and WOW! So, so, so good. We have come to Nami several times for coffee and donuts but have never tried the cake. I'm gluten free and my husband is vegan, so not the easiest feat to find something special for our wedding. I'm a pastry chef and I wasn't thrilled about making my own cake, so Nami it was! Delicious and beautifully frosted. A perfect end to our special day!

yjLVolBvIicYo07JE3q5lQ.text: Been here a couple of times. Good coffee and food. Great HUGE oatmeal cookies. I would honestly come here for the cookies alone.

PRCUJf0gZ-F-sSKqMEIUpw.text: Great little coffee stop with delicious vegan pastries. Staff were friendly and atmosphere was laid back.

s3zlY4LUtNYR77_XtgK8uQ.text: Right next door to Green so afterward I took my boys for "ice cream". Fantastic! Still not sure what we had but we all loved it. Price was great too, $8 bucks for all 3 of us.  I noticed other Yelpers complained about the service but our experience was great. Very accommodating and they even made chocolate chip (not on menu) for us.

5t2nXhg0us-uYCeC_nygbQ.text: The zebra donut- THATS ALL I HAVE TO SAY!! it's vegan, and still delicious and  beautiful!! the icing is perfect, it's just moist enough. I've been craving it every day since! I've been twice now and gotten an iced caramel macchiato both times and a donut. The coffees have consistantly been watered down. Not the best unfortunately, but the donuts make up for it.

Y-dU5mjESbt1VopXyVznZQ.text: Today is my second day in row coming here for breakfast. Yesterday, I ordered the Nami McBagel Breakfast Sandwich and the Matcha Green Tea Latte. The breakfast sandwich was crazy good! I'm not a vegan so I was a little skeptical of the tofu egg, "bacon" and "cheese", but it was absolutely delicious! There is also a sauce that is a little spicy which completes this sandwich. I also love that they use real matcha as many places don't and I can get  it unsweetened, which a lot of people think is crazy.  The only downfall is the cost. It's $16.83 for a breakfast sandwich and latte. To me, that's a bit expensive. This is a place I'll come back to splurge every now and again, though. The food and I cannot forget the service is that good!  Highly recommend!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Real matcha green tea latte

BrkPe20qa5rUHAL0XPJatg.text: Vegan what? Where? I brought my very picky boyfriend to this place to try a treat, I didn't tell him it was a vegan place well into him eating his dessert. He was shocked, he didn't believe me, he thought it was so good and said he was definitely fooled. I had a cinnamon roll, and I too was unable to tell the difference. A delicious late night treat.

DoV7fRVZp1yVysRX_Sc_7Q.text: Love how many gluten free options they have! It's the only place my gf son can get an ice cream cone. Their donuts are the best I've ever had. Their brunch is great too, but get there early because the line wraps around the building and parking is very limited.

qN0GLJ2MEA0Szrydh1eDnw.text: Stopped in for some ice cream. THE BEST ICE CREAM I HAVE EVER HAD!!! Banana cream pie & Life's a peach was amazing

41Bh8rBIe4ZaiwjGvcNaQw.text: I always try to frequent small local vegan restaurants on my business travels. Nami did not disappoint. Friendly staff, fast service, clean facility and the food was amazing! I had the breakfast burrito and I'm not sure I'll need lunch after this! Great coffee as well. I didn't have any of the vegan donuts but they looked great and I'll be sure to grab one next time I'm in town.

ChUDcYDuliBkj32G9YZ0Zg.text: My husband and I have been going to Nami and its counterpart (Green New American Vegetarian) for years. Despite my husband not being a big lover of vegan food, we both absolutely love anything we've tried on their ever-rotating menu! Most recently, we placed a catering order with Nami to have some of their world class donuts be delivered as a late night snack for our wedding guests. The order arrived exactly as described, and our guests (most of which are not vegan) raved about how fresh and tasty the donuts were, not to mention how beautifully decorated they looked! I am so glad we went with Nami for our special wedding day dessert, and can't recommend this restaurant enough, whether it be for a quick casual bite or a large catering order!

y8TIZE6LXsc2K6Aa2Ob6XA.text: Amazing vegan desserts and breakfast! On Sunday's you can ask for your burrito Changa style and it's awesome but very heavy. The service is always welcoming as well. They tend to be busy during the weekends so expect a little longer wait, but it's worth it. Love their Dough boy!

MqHuA3-AljlQHm7PTCnRug.text: I loves Nami. I ordered a cup of peanut butter, which was da bomb!! So delicious. I was SO close to getting the Flying Saucer, but it was my mom's..and I didn't know... Everyone was so nice to me! I love vegans!???!!  -Rex

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

LUi3NnxSd3V6wbND4WChWw.text: I've been eating at Green for seven years, so when the building for Nami was purchased fairly recently, I was excited to see what they would do with it! Their vegan soft serve has always been incredible and you can get it at both of the Green restaurants, but what I love about Nami is that they have A LOT of different baked goods and beverages! I no longer live in Arizona, so when I visit family, I always have to stop by to purchase a box of treats. Their Yankee Doodles are amazing, as well as everything else I've ever had there. The parking is atrocious and you're better off parking elsewhere and just walking to the restaurant if you plan on sitting and not just sending someone in the pick something up for you.

4DLLp8zY6ENB9dMfEyCXsg.text: I only stopped in to grab dessert and I gotta admit it was a difficult choice but we opted for their chocolate cake, it was a nice big size and felt really dense in the box they put it in. Got home and WOW! I will be getting this cake again, it was moist, chocolatey, and delicious. I'd love to bring some friends/family here that think Vegan things always taste weird because they'd never imagine how good it can be. Looking forward to coming back to Nami and trying out some of their specialty drinks and other snacks. Parking lot was pretty busy and tight but we managed to find a little spot. Just be patient, it's worth coming in. Been back a few more times & their donuts are Amazing! Also I LOVE their S'mores Tsoynami, wow!!! Always super busy parking lot when I go, of course their food is Insanely dee-lish.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Chocolate cake w/chocolate frosting to go. Absolutely dense, delicious, moist &amp; flavorful. Yum!

0eOQ47dk4nWKmkBmezY6zQ.text: I doscovered the little gem in my search to find a new breakfast place. I was delighted to see such great reviews by other Yelpers.  I pulled onto the parking lot and was directed by an employee that the blue building is not Nami, but the one next door. Helpful as the two share a parking lot.  The inside of Nami is quaint with retro fruniture and art mixed in with little cacti in the windowsills and proud displays that they are open to all.  The menu stretches across the wall and features assorted coffee drinks, pastries and a lovely hot breakfast menu. From what I could tell, all of the items are organic.  I ordered a samoan but received a samoan bar instead of samoan donut instead. This was quickly remedied by the friendly cashier. The hot chocolate was also delightful with almond milk, my favorite.  They also had a small offering of other items such as boxed crackers, cookies, candy, etc.  Their restroom out back was decorated in a modern style.  The prices are comparable to the chain coffee shops and I would much rather shop local!

Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Samoan Bar
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. More interior

BFUXebxQfUC9rlguoAR2aQ.text: One of my favorite shops in town! Workers have been friendly every time I've been there. Soynami!!!!!! Love the vegan pastries here but the soy based soft serve is to die for and you don't feel guilty after. I usually get the Oreo but you can pick or add your own choice of topping to make that perfect sweet delight. It's a large serving so sometimes I share with a friend.

Zci8v-9B6BbyjV0bqXy7Sg.text: Went in for an iced coffee and came out with a mediocre drink for $7 before tip. I'm sorry, I like to support local, but not when it's double the cost and the quality is mediocre. A couple behind me was going to get a bag with about two handfuls of granola in it, but chose to leave instead when they were told it was $8. Come on, now? Let people support you. All you have to be is reasonable. When a couple goes out of there way to go to your shop and leaves with nothing based on your ridiculous pricing after I almost choked hearing the price of my drink... that says something.

4BS8wEfNHP4XW54gw2DqQA.text: The best vegan McFlurry-type thing you will ever have. I got the doughboy- vanilla ice cream with COOKIE DOUGH. I always get the same thing. My parents got the Monsoon tsoynami which had delicious, moist dark chocolate cake mixed in with the ice cream. So yummy!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

9Qr4wygmHTZbxbBdgCJ9aA.text: I'm not a vegan by any means by I am impressed every time! They put a lot of work in making the meat substitutes taste like real meat. They're portions are huge too. So any stereotype you have of not getting full from eating Vegan food is 100% False! I leave here happy every time!

pvLWoLGiRy9O5UhGVmjEDw.text: Super Yummy!! Casual, child-friendly environment with tasty breakfast and drinks. The pastries looked amazing too with a really large assortment. The vegan country breakfast burrito I had was very large and I didn't eat again until dinner. So nice to be able to order anything I wanted off the menu, a rare treat for vegans! I would definitely go back again.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Trying Nami because I&#39;ve heard great things!

LkDyvQbcrs7TYSFDNouiog.text: This was one of the famous places I wanted to try for dessert in Phoenix.  The place is a vegan soft serve place with lots of other baked goods.  The soft serve had many interesting flavors, I got the chai tiramisu, since it sounded delicious and a great combo of flavors.  The flavor itself was really good and the price was pretty reasonable considering the quality.  It was 5 dollars for a small cup, but pretty good.  There is a small area for parking in the back!

If you're in town, do yourself a favor and check this place out!

ipk6_nZQkvvtyhpvJYNufg.text: You guys!!!! The vegan ice cream is life changing. I've been baptized in the vegan waters and I'm a believer.  Believe me- if you get stomach aches from dairy your going to be converted! This stuff is holly. Hallelujah!

3LYKbxRKA6FYfDbQrYP23g.text: I was craving a Soy-Nami the entire drive from Vegas. Was NOT disappointed. Sooo good. Kiddo like his dessert too.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Mint soynami on the top left, no-nos candy and then a cupcake. My son did not really love the cupcake but he liked stealing my soynami

hxYmFKzlVtAh7i0DAPC7CQ.text: This place is right by work so it is a regular stop. Staff is friendly and service is fast. In the summer the tsoynami is a yummy treat, especially the rocky road. The rest of the year I treat myself to a latte or an Italian soda and a sweet treat like a cupcake or other pastry.  Try the strawberry agave Italian soda....delicious!

1DmHn1xdUj9qv8omhHdQkg.text: I wanted to love this place but it just didn't impress me all that much. I came to try out their doughnuts. I got there at opening and the doughnuts weren't out so I had to wait around. Ended up getting a chocolate banana doughnut which was just okay - if you're looking for a vegan baked doughnut Urban Cookies just down the road has much better tasting doughnuts (imo). Also got a "clunky monkey" tsoynami - this was pretty good except for the fact that it was more pecans than ice cream. Overall not bad but not enough to make me want to go back.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. clunky monkey tsoynami &amp; chocolate banana doighnut

03hhVTHdUTJj0MRT3gTpsA.text: On the same night my friend and I went to Green, we stopped here to get some vegan sweets.  We decided on cookies.  I think she ordered a snickerdoodle, and I ordered a chocolate chip cookie.  The cookies were good; however, it took a bit of time for us to get them.  They were right in the case, and I'd say we waited a good 10 minutes or so, and not sure why it took that long for us to receive them.  On my last day in Phoenix, we returned here to each try a tSoynami treat.  She had the banana cream pie flavor, and I ordered the PB and chocolate, and we were both LOVING our treats!  Very yummy and excellent to cool you down on a hot Arizona day!  Will also be back on my next trip.

ReFfz824HojgHvDgy4zvTA.text: Vegan doughnuts and breakfast, coffee, tea and some specialty drinks. No smoothies or protein shakes which I would like to see but I've never been disappointed here -we need more of these in the valley. High quality and delicious!

u8unKMaN62wHwk9jrRSXZg.text: Hands down best ice cream in Phoenix. Creatively delicious vegan mixes that consist of classics as well as seasonal additions (Pumpkin pie mix is to die for). Always leaves your gut feeling good too!

RXsH6EKeNkIgdgs_3xanGg.text: Nami and Green's are the place to be if you're a vegetarian and you're looking for some creative vegetarian cuisine. It's not uncommon for vegetarians and vegans alike to struggle to find quality meals outside of their own kitchen that satisfy nutritional need as well as great taste - at Nami and Green's you won't have that problem. On Sundays, enjoy a brunch by Nami and seating in Greens - bring your non-vegetarian friends and enjoy a meal that's appropriate and delicious for everyone. Get there early however - parking is competitive!

KTrh9v8wyDGt_54cU4ydMw.text: Last time coming to Nami- the 10 minute drive was not worth it and here is why..... It's vegan great but its mostly processed, high sugar, and over priced compared to competitors. I stopped going to green vegetarian a long time ago. But now Nami is on the list. I would go in here occasionally for a yogurt parfait. Now it's 1/2 the quantity and for the same price. Oh and for a TBS of extra granola they charge $2. Yeah I'm done. This has been the consensus among the people I know that used to go here also... it's all processed high sugar appeasing but yeah not worth it. It's not a conscious vegan places based on nutrient dense plant based foods that can be delicious when sweetened properly. Nevertheless I kept coming for that 1 thing which would be a cookie, drink, etc here and there. Well that's it for me. I applaud the idea but update your business marketing and retention provisions to keeping customers and you will keep booming. Don't......  well continue to loose an existing customer base- which btw is extremely important long term . That's just the business of the restaurants.

BwrhX1Peq5Krm5Ae_y0Pkw.text: I live in Portland but my family is in Phoenix, so I visit often. I absolutely love this place! It feels like I found a little bit of Portland there. The staff is super attentive and the food is so delicious. I love showing off how yummy vegan food can be to my family!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Brunch before flying back home. So good!

kzYOwkxSAHd4_EGveXrUrg.text: A vegan restaurant...the menu is limited and a little on the pricey side... but isn't everything else in the country?!    The faux eggs and sausage was surprisingly good!   If you don't want one of their drinks.. you can have water and ice in the back, near the kitchen area.   There's two restrooms outside, and they're very clean and modern.   Parking is very bad st this place... its like parking in an alleyway.   There wasn't any parking, so we parked in the restaurant a couple of doors down (no one ticketed us or put a warning, etc.   I'm sure they're use to it by now).

k-i9LUBoX_XqKas9i4uM9Q.text: As if the Tsoynami's weren't good enough, I tried brunch here for the first time this weekend and it was soooo good. I got the Benedict as a plate - tofu scramble, asparagus, tempeh bacon and hollandaise served over chibatta bread. I also got the Cactus Haboob Latte - agave and cinnamon infused and it was to die for. Vegan or not, go to this place!   It fills up quick though, so get there early or expect a little wait!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Benedict - so good!

ppsmg9jTDXpN9QWlzV3k1g.text: Super, super, super yummy!  Just because everything they serve is vegan doesn't mean is less calories. We splurged today for our anniversary and I had a doughnut and my husband had a piece of cake and a latte. Oh my gosh, this is the BEST vegan dessert I have ever had!!

NE0wtN504zrwhVZFMNCZuw.text: Came here since my stay at AZ was situated within walking distance to this location. Needless to say I was blown away, I don't think I had anything else within those two days. I tried the breakfast burrito with the veggie nuggets, tsoynami cookie dough and the veggie eggs Benedict. These aren't your traditional dishes as they are replaced with tofu and no meat, but boy were they amazing. The burrito was perfectly seasoned with just the right amount of cumin. The tofu looked just like eggs. The tsoynami was probably the best soft serve, thought it melts pretty easily I love how it has the texture of soft serve but not the overwhelming taste of milk. I would definitely recommend this place

myC-hCZMq3pKURimSvZLwg.text: This place was so amazing. I had a vegan dirty chai doughnut with an iced chai and it was delicious. The staff was really nice and friendly. Cute atmosphere. At first I was confused where to park but there is parking in the back of the building. If you're vegan/vegetarian you need to check this place out.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Iced chai with a dirty chai doughnut.

w-BOzFp2Aewm7VSGmSfkCQ.text: I have no idea why this place has such high reviews - I tried it based on the high rating but it was insanely disappointing. It's trendy more than quality, the desserts are pretty decent but sickly sweet and a bit steep on the pricing. The "coffee" is a whole different story, it's NOT coffee at all, it's a bunch of sugar, syrup and cinnamon/nutmeg. I'd rather support small coffee shops and bakeries with quality products and pricing in sunnyslope than this garbage. I assume the people drinking "coffee" here have no clue what real coffee tastes like.

cl1QUJ3OClYCz-xJqt_9VQ.text: Delightful!  After visiting Green New American next door, we thought it would be nice to finish off a wonderful meal with a wonderful dessert.  In a word:  Wow!  Even if you didn't save room for dessert, it is worth ignoring that little voice in your head telling you moderation is a good thing.  Moderation can wait until tomorrow, but these sweet treats cannot!

I1yIacI-fEBnSibdkieTyA.text: For those with allergies or food sensitivities, Nami is a great place to go to! I had the tsoynami with a friend as a treat, and it was so good. I had the Coffee Coco Loco tsoynami, which came with chocolate, coffee, and little pieces of crispy rice. My friend had the Almond Oy Vey, which came with coconut flakes, chocolate syrup, and almond silvers. Keep in mind that both of these "ice cream" were gluten free and dairy free, and it was amazing how good it tasted! The tsoynamis were a bit lighter and icier than their traditional heavier icecream counterparts, but I liked it better the tsoynami way.   Nami also has quiche, pastries, shakes, yogurt parfaits, gluten free donuts, as well as vegan donuts and brunch on select days.   Will be definitely going back to try their gluten free donuts and their parfaits before work, and definitely will be back for some tsoynami treats - I'll post pictures! In a happy food coma right now... Highly recommended.

Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Coffee Coco Loco tsoynami- really delicious! gluten free, dairy free

8TP-SxUD4d8C2zlO2_BiOg.text: I ordered a tSoynami and really enjoyed it. They have a great selection of creations that you can order from. The only problem I run into here is that this place can be tight squeeze and your order can take awhile on busy nights.

eFFr5BmSEdDI8ogp-gCoIg.text: Outrageous line with no accommodation for a typical busy Sunday morning. Spoke to the manager who had no apologies and really had a snooty pretentious entitled attitude. And wow $43 for 3 burritos!! The soy burger was not good.

WjkbbIqjh6tecZtS1C-cgg.text: Nami is the perfect all vegan place for a treat during the crazy AZ summers! Their tsoynamis never disappoint and with so many options for mix ins, you can try something new every time you go! The chocolate soft serve is my favorite (they also have vanilla or swirl) and their ricemellow fluff is the yummiest mix in! I also absolutely love their vegan donuts and am so happy that they always have at least one gluten free option to choose from. The only thing that I'm not a huge fan of is the coffee which is very acidic and has an odd aftertaste.

WUh_H_lP9Z6QAQfh_2UD_w.text: Nami, oh me oh my! Oh Na- Mi! Nami is one of favorite hidden gems in downtown Phoenix! It's hidden on the corner of the historic neighborhood around Garfield and Coronado I believe. It's also right next to Phoenix Green which is an awesome Vegetarian/ vegan based restaurant! Good food but that's a different review for another day! Nami also serves as a coffee shop, so get specialty coffee lovely vegan pastries at your service. What they are mostly known for is their yummy donuts and they have an awesome brunch that they do on Sunday's which is superb. But when you go, definitely is try one of their signature tsyonami which is a yogurt based soft serve made with coconut / soy products so all vegan safe! From the cute small interior that's filled with local artists art, and cute little succulents. Nami is a way to go or at least try out, it surely won't disappoint! Ok Arizona stay hungry and keep being cool!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. BETTERFINGER TSOYNAMI SWIRL

aHtAxqfxiCgZY0iJF7Tt2g.text: This place is so witty as you see in reading the menu. I have yet to try the vegan pastries, but I can certainly vouch for the vegan soft serve! My favorite so far is the Soy Capitan with vanilla soft serve. Another bonus is you can create your own tsoynami!

ZtltAVantdMNFiAX_3YZjw.text: I was recently on a trip to Phoenix and we decided to check out nami for dessert after lunch next door at Green New American Vegetarian. We were a little too full for a tSoynami so we each had one blueberry fritter (large donut hole size). They were very good! We went and did some sightseeing and came back (only slightly shamefully) a couple hours later for tSoynamis. I had the Doughboy (vanilla soft serve, chocolate sauce, and cookie dough) and my companion had the Donatello (vanilla soft serve, caramel, chocolate sauce, chocolate chips, and pecans). These were like I remember Blizzards being! Soooo good. I haven't had anything like it since I became vegan 11 years ago. I would be in serious trouble if I lived in Phoenix since once upon on a time I had a serious Blizzard / DQ addiction. Please come to Portland, maybe? :)

LSSyn6ki28yJrAZCpAslsQ.text: I LOVE this place! I've been here twice so far and each time it has been amazing! There usually is never a wait, and if there is it goes by really quick. All the employees are super friendly and nice. The place itself isn't huge but there is a lot of seating for everyone inside and outside which is nice! Also nice, they have restrooms right outside by the entrance! I've tried the doughboy tsoynami and also the PB 'n' Chocolate and they are both delicious! The prices aren't too high but you do get what you pay for! I haven't tried anything else on the menu but everything looks delicious here! I definitely will be returning back in the future!

JOiytytUkSRPK6BaeJbA_w.text: I would probably give this place a solid 3 or 4 just for existing! But, it bothers me greatly that the staff doesn't know what is in the food. When I asked what they use in the lemon bars the response was "I have no idea". I came in again with my friend, and we both ordered tsoynami. They made his first, then a bunch of other people- nearly 19 minutes later mine was ready. My friend tried to wait to eat his, but it was melting. So, by the time I had mine- I was eating alone. It really didn't make sense.   Conclusion- a vegan restaurant should really know what's in the food. Many people adopt this lifestyle because of food allergies and various other concerns. Improve workflow and service. Right now you are below standard, but you have the potential to be great.

YMpzJ6DuNdUEqgTdQ7tRBw.text: I hit up Nami twice while in Arizona - once for a famed tsoynami (a vegan twist on a Dairy Queen blizzard), second time for breakfast.  It's such a great gem in the desert, and I love that it's right by where my only friend in the area lives, haha.  The second I started crossing through Phoenix (after 7 hours on the road!), I found my way to Nami to get a cookies and cream tsoynami.  It's a cute little bungalow with way more parking than I anticipated - except this place is popular so it's still not enough, haha.  Everyone working there is so sweet and upbeat, you can't help but be in a good mood, too.  I got my treat and headed to my final destination in Scottsdale.  I found the vanilla soft serve base really disappointing.  It was really icy and melted almost instantly.  It's not the creamy, thick base of blizzards or McFlurries I remember at all.  But it was cold, and I was hot, at the cookie bits throughout were perfect.  I was determined to give them another try on my way out of Phoenix, to grab breakfast before my journey home.  This time, I went with a caramel "mockiato" and a McBagel Sandwich.  10 outta 10, on both counts!  The mockiato was a dead ringer for my former favorite at Starbucks, with a little whipped cream and everything!  I'll be real, my sweet tooth has subsided these past few years (maybe thanks to veganism?!), but this was such a treat and the perfect trip down memory lane.  I also looooooved the McBagel Sandwich.  I've got a soft spot for breakfast sandwiches and this was one of the best I've had.  Fried eggy tofu, veg ham, cheddar daiya (I think?),  and spicy aioli on a bagel tasted like something out of my LA favorite, locali, except fully loaded.  I headed on the road to California right after, and didn't need to stop for food the whole way.  That's impressive!  I'd definitely come back here when I'm in the area!  They have so many vegan goodies, that even if the tsoynamis don't impress me, I will not leave empty handed (uhhh s'mores bars and twinkies, anybody?).

2jGvXevTGF8gKv0IAPKY2w.text: For over a year now I have oogled over pictures of food from Nami and today I went and tried my first tSoynami. My expectations were definitely met! I have been trying to stay away from dairy lately, but sometimes vegan treats just aren't that good. Not the case at Nami! The location was easy to find, but parking was horrible. I think I parked illegally and almost hit a wall and a few cars trying to get in and out of a spot. But that is my only complaint! The place is smaller than I had anticipated, but it was cute! Not too crowded, but there was a steady flow of people. I liked both the interior and exterior of the restaurant. At first I was worried because the tsoynamis weren't written on the chalk board, but then I thankfully found a menu. There were so many options! A lot of gluten free choices as well which is so great. I certainly had trouble choosing. Also they had some ready made treats on display which looked tasty. Some kind of coconut donut, yum! After much deliberation, I settled on the Haystack Attack. I got half chocolate half vanilla. It came with chocolate, gluten free pretzels, rice marshmallow, and a rice cereal. It was very very tasty! Very sweet and I couldn't finish it, but I loved it and would totally come back to try something new. Also now I'm looking at the Sunday brunch pictures and I'm drooling over them. Another positive, the people working there were nice, didn't seem pretentious, which sometimes people who work at places like that kind of are ha. Very awesome, I recommend!

a76WR0Vp_9oR7pe_oO9LHw.text: I'm not into healthyish stuff, but holy Jesus... I loved my ice cream here. It was vanilla soy and coconut milk ice cream but it didn't have a weird chalky texture or coconut flavor. It is more watery than ice cream made with cow milk when it melts. But it wasn't full of ice crystals like a granita. It still has a great smooth texture.   I had the banana cream pie tsoynami. It had bananas, banana syrup, whipped cream and vanilla cookies. I wish I had a second cup of just the vanilla cookies. It was exactly what I was craving that I didn't even know until I put it in my mouth.   Who knew healthyish stuff could taste so good?  At this point, I'll just pretend like it's all fat free so I can try everything. I can't wait to go back.   The only caveat? The parking lot is small & was packed even during what was supposedly their "slow time". So, carpool or walk or ride a bike maybe? But don't miss out on this awesome place.

V37I1qZWLiP4ZBZVtPcJQg.text: I bought two items here, a slice of the Pistachio Rose Cake and a Coffee Cake donut. The cake slice was moist and baked well, also frosted beautifully, I thought for the amount the price was reasonable. I bought it for lunch and I was full! I bought a coworker the Coffee Cake donut and she liked it. The parking situation is tight and small so be careful and you can only enter on the South side of the building and you exit on the North side.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. The pistachio rose cake. Around $5. It reminded me of marzipan and cardamom.

QXL-YxwGZD5wzPlTH-BHsg.text: LOVE EVERYTHING ABOUT THIS PLACE! All Vegan. You have to try their ice cream blizzards! All different flavors, only $5. I got the s'mores and I came back and got the cookie dough too. Both so good! They have vanilla, chocolate or twist. Of course, you don't have to get the blizzard. You could get just get an ice cream cone or cup too. I loved this place so much that I came back yet again for their breakfast! We got the special which was a breakfast pizza. Such big portions! Didn't end up trying any of their sweets but they looked delicious! Also had plenty of gluten free options. They have a very SMALL parking lot. Staff was very friendly. Bathrooms located outside. Only downside was they charge more for almond milk in my house brew coffee. LIKE WHY?! You are an all vegan cafe. That being said that was my only compliant. Great vegan cafe!

rXNuLrbug8w1GZnrrsuliw.text: YUMMY!! As a lactose intolerant person this is my go-to place for ice cream cravings and milk shakes. Can't go wrong with the dough boy tsoynami! It may be a 15 minute drive from my house, but it is SO worth it. You will not be disappointed!

AZIBUlqevfD-GpoZJ8OLDw.text: I'm not vegan, but I brought some friends who were visiting and have recently become vegan.  They absolutely loved it.  There was a large group of us there for breakfast so we had the chance to try several different things.  Friends loved their biscuits and gravy and I liked my breakfast burrito, although next time I'll probably skip the melty vegan cheese.  Everything is vegan and they have gluten free options on top of that so I'll definitely be taking some family there when they come to visit (multiple allergies/food sensitivities).  Their donuts were light and fluffy, unlike other vegan pastries I've had.  Can't wait to come back to try some of their other desserts and coffee drinks.  The best surprise was the pitaya bowl.  The puree is so light and refreshing and goes well with the granola and fruit on top.  It was even better than the acai bowl another friend tried.  I don't know that I would go for any savory items again if I didn't have any vegans with me, but I'll definitely be back for coffee, dessert and pastries and probably the pitaya bowl!  We're also sad we missed the special brunch.  I guess they only serve that on certain days.  I would have liked to try their pancakes and French toast.

9ubmgx__m-Yhi0RMj20c0Q.text: Delicious, even as someone who is not a vegan.  The atmosphere is great and the coffee rivals some of the exclusively coffee-serving shops in Phoenix.    That, and any place that serves tsoynamis are officially a favorite of mine.

jWUcl-nrkJ3NV9kOlGJBTA.text: tsoynami. some crazy vegan cold stone blizzard. they make their own vegan soft serve and it's actually very good. you can pick all sorts of things to mix into it and it's delicious. They have tons of donuts, baked goods, and coffee drinks.

Pmzb17ZKj27fMv9__1s3nw.text: Nami recently did our wedding cake and a variety of pies for our April 2013 wedding. We had a carrot cake with cream cheese frosting for our cake and 10 fruit/pecan pies. They were all amazing! We had 65 people at our wedding and didn't tell anyone they were vegan. No one would had known otherwise. My husband's mother, who is an amazing cook herself and doesn't dole out compliments lightly, said it was the best pecan pie she had ever had. We did not have many leftovers at the dessert table to say the least. A big thank you to Nami!

qtR0oKN182X_9lDKiXMnBQ.text: Yeah!   Love this place!!  Went for coffee, nothing special an Americano...it was so creamy and delicious!  Wonder what they use for soy milk?  While I was there, directly after eating at green, I could not resist the soy soft serve tsunami...hope I'm spelling that right.  Chocolate and peanut butter with chocolate chips, so awesome!  Makes me want to move downtown so I can go to Nami at least once a day!

3d0qureBZpuQ__5Nq7k5_Q.text: Haven't been here in awhile, cause I drive from the far East Valley.  Used to be my go to when I was on this side of town and would normally have good service.  Unfortunately today was not a good experience. We ordered two coffees and two doughnuts, simple order. I waited forever to get my order. Everyone behind me in line that ordered, got theirs and left. I noticed they made all the Tsoynamis all at once, no matter what time you ordered them. Leaving all the simple orders at the end, even though I was first to order. I had to ask if they forgot me, since I was the last man standing. They said no, we're making your drinks now. They asked if I already got my pastries, I told them that I haven't received anything from them and I waited the longest. Not one sorry...no apologies, nada. Where has the customer service gone.... As business owners I understand that you're only as good as your product and especially customer service. Unfortunately they failed in customer service today. I believe their system is flawed, hopefully they're having an off day. One customer told me that this was the longest wait he's ever experienced and he had just ordered a simple plain iced coffee, he got his order right before mine, after he had to remind them of it. Was going to give them 2 stars for today's experience, but thought that may be a bit harsh.

(i miss that granola) we also tried this vegan gluten free cheesecake WOW! all the employees were super hip and FRIENDLY! great time thanks for providing vegan treats to phoenix

2QsL7cTiJzoqg7qTcwYleg.text: I never knew Vegan sweets could taste so good. The tSoynamis are amazing particularly the classic peanut butter and chocolate flavor combination.  These tSoynamis are similar to a blizzard in the sense that it is a soft serve type ice cream with mix ins...that's when comparisons end though.  The ice cream here is vegan although the texture isn't quite as soft as traditional soft serve it's still pretty smooth on the whole.  The baked goods are also quite delicious and quite massive.  The prices are a little on the high side though and would add up quickly if one came here all the time for a coffee or dessert. Still need to try the brunch.

cfMuZpd3C3GAYU1D4Z35bg.text: Great place for vegan delight!   If your looking for a vegan friendly coffee / dessert spot in CenPho, I can think of none better than Nami. I came here for the Tsoynami (a vegan friendly dq blizzard) and was not dissapointed. While I don't think you can ever really compare apples to apples when it comes to dairy desserts and non dairy alternatives, it's about as close as you will find. (I wonder if they have one with apples? probably not). I don't think I will ever really find a replacement for my froyo love.  I can't attest for how healthy they are; I imagine the fat content is fairly low, since it is soy based. For those carb / sugar conscious - the ingredients info isn't really posted anywhere, but I imagine there is a fair amount of sugar in whatever toppings, cookies, and candies that go into your frozen dessert. Just do a couple extra sit-ups, it's worth it!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Cookies n creme tsoynami with peanut butter

jl1xUV_SRiJncWGOX_NunQ.text: I'm a fan of cool, hip coffee places and to find a place like this in PHX was gravy!   After finishing up a road trip vacay of the four corners states, a much needed iced cold coffee back home to Los Angeles would be nice. Especially when your in this Arizona desert heat Nami can't go wrong and thanks to my trusted Yelp search this place made me feel like hipster home.  Parking can be tight here and we ended up parking at the rear. There is a rear entrance way to get inside if you are parking from the backside of the shop. Why I like hipster joints like these? its because many offer different types of coffee in their special menu, not just ordinary and I like the cool savvy ambiance.   It was on a sunday here close to brunch time it was packed here, and hell no we are not getting out this line! Patience is worthy here trust me. Looking at their menu on the wall they do have an impressive variety from deserts, hot coffee or cold but most of all its Vegan powered here!   We ordered the Caramel Mochaito and the Cactus Haboob ( not sure if its spelled exactly right )  but their specials had names like "the Mash" among others. Im not sure what our iced coffees had in them but the name says it all and what really matters is the taste. Our drinks were $5.00 each. which is cool, you gotta remember VEGAN.  The staff here are pros because we didn't wait too long for our orders and the place was busy. After taking a few sips of our drinks, it wasn't overly sweet with any sugar rush or any of that coffee bitterness, all I can say is that both our drinks tasted smooth especially the Caramel Moch. I had was silk as Dove chocolate and the Cactus Haboob was cool and refreshing like Freddy Flintstone's Cactus Coola.  Checkout their other desserts here they look eye candy and promising. I highly recommend coming to Nami and to do away the Starbucks! Think Vegan!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Caramel Mochiatto and Cactus Haboob.

pxw0v3U8rKGzA2MTzwx7mg.text: Other than the limited seating, I have nothing but good things to say about this place.  You will not regret it.

EUpKFv-XmKgwXVxus4B_dA.text: It takes a great deal to push me to review an establishment, good or otherwise and I have written few.  Whenever I'm in town, Green has been my standby for a couple of years now for its vegan selections, and this time around I took my family to Nami for the first time. For starters, my tea had finally come out with no almond milk. Easy fix. Didn't think anything of it. Brunch is a busy time for them and can understand that there are many chances for mistakes, however we noticed after a while that guests who ordered well after us were finishing their meals. We followed up and got an apology and we were fine with the explanation of their miscommunication within the kitchen. So to pass the time, I had ordered a mimosa from green and asked for different juice option. ($7 for a less than an 8oz mason jar). The lady misunderstood my order that I had already paid for and when I saw her finishing the pour of oj, I tried to explain that wasn't what I meant at all. Her reply "I already poured it." No matter that I already paid for it tho, right? She served the mimosa with a side cup and I asked her what that was for. She explained that the cup was for the juice order. Clearly another mix up and she refunded me for the juice. 20 min later, our food had finally arrived. I asked for the chiliquiles with no potatoes and it showed up loaded with potatoes. I pointed it out to our server, again, very apologetic and willing to correct it and add more scramble in place of. No problem there, except it came back with potatoes on it still. I had then asked to make a new one since their idea of a remedy was to simply remove the potatoes, and our server agreed to my request. The order came back with a hair on the plate and my moms fruit also had a hair. That said and also after tipping generously at the time of order, I decided to ask for a manager from Green. As it happens the cashier who took my mimosa order was the manager. I took her aside away from the table to explain our experience had been unusually below par and that I am a loyal customer. Her response was one that lacked empathy and not even made any kind of act or offer of righting the wrongs of the experience. And at that point, i knew what I had to do. Thank you for reading and I hope others get better service/treatment than we did.   As for myself, my friends and family who I recommend, these two establishments has seen my last dime and now what was once a recommendation will now be a that of a warning.

I7hkjJQfF1J1nmKbGWv-dw.text: Pleasantly surprising.  They serve Royal (@ the Market), for those interested.  Being pretty hip to the coffee scene in PHX, I was a little surprised to hear of this new shop, having not heard of it's coming.  Maybe I didn't look around enough, but it felt like Nami just kind of popped up.  So I had my doubts, as I always will when giving a new place a shot.  The layout was pleasant, and the decor pretty rad; love the couch.  Parking seems sorted out a great deal better than when That's A Wrap inhabited the area -  good plus there.  Sweets looked great.  So I order my typical - drip and a 2x (on the side).  This gives me a general idea of the shop; milk drinks are for second and beyond trips.  Firstly, their demi-tasses are super cute.  Obviously hand-made, and hopefully local.  Loved it.  My drip actually turned out to be a pour-over, which is a plus to me.  A coffee junkie can appreciate a pour-over, where it kind of scares a person just wanting some "coffee" (see: I understand why you call it drip vs pour-over).  Straight up espresso is generally a quick way of determining bad-average-good.  Crema was nice though, consistent, and had me thinking I might have a decent thing here.  Taste was good, creamy and quite chocolatey (which seems the profile of the beans being used - the drip was reminiscent of the same).  Said and done (from a 'snob' standpoint), the espresso was good, not mindblowing.  I think the grind was right, but either the dosing could be moved up a tiny bit, or tamped a little harder.  Granted, this was the first and only I had there, so I can't necessarily base the entire shop on that one dopio.  All in all, I'm saying it was good, and while the extraction time was right, it could use a little more density.  The drip (see: pour-over) clearly used the same roast, which isn't a complaint.  The same chocolatey, creamy notes were abound.  I feel the dosing was very light, and should have either been a 12oz, or more grounds used.  I actually felt I was drinking a water heavy coffee.  Not terrible, but certainly not great.  I have a sneaking suspicion if the measurement was a bit closer, it would have been a much better brew.  Pour-overs are an art first, for sure, then a science.  I think they have potential here.  Maybe a better pot would help with this brew method as well.  -- I'll be back.  My experience was neither mind-blowing nor off-putting.  I'm hoping after they get into the swing of things and get the kinks ironed out, this will be one of the cooler stops in PHX.  Certainly a great concept and whatnot.

0bLC3r2LTSl4FpLjFNlfBQ.text: This is such a cute coffee shop. My husband, two children, and I went for Sunday morning coffee and doughnuts. I ordered the Cactus Haboob and my husband ordered a Dirty Chai Latte. We also ordered Blueberry Coconut and White Chocolate/Dark Chocolate doughnuts. The coffee and doughnuts were awesome! I don't usually go downtown Phoenix, but this little excursion felt like a touristy getaway for the morning. It will take a little time for the baristas to get your order to you when there is actually a line out the door, but that didn't bother us. I highly recommend everyone to try this place out.

XivrkHTeme6fCtOFIp2CiQ.text: Ok. Since I've become completely and totally addicted to tsoynamis, it's only fair that I update my review. At least once a week I find myself craving a tsoynami. Even my boyfriend, who is adamantly against vegan and soy products, has fallen in love with the tsoynamis and often accompanies me on my trips to get them. These desserts are also HUGE. ctCTHouBRwe88Gc-lrMP-A.text: So goooooooood  After Jon S. introduced me to tsoynamis at Green in Scottsdale, a few friends decided to stop by on our way back to Tempe from Bliss. I was surprised to find a cute little cafe next to Green. The guy at the register was super friendly, and helped my friend decide what flavor to get. As expected, the tsoynami was amazing and I'll definitely be back if I'm in the area.

J8Xv47ghnYrTzu5UcpQG-g.text: I take back my previous review. Over time I have tried different options at Nami and it has become a favorite place for me. You get quite a bit of soy ice cream for your money - usually more than I can eat in one sitting and they now have chocolate soy ice cream as well. My favorites are the Dough Boy and Almond Oy Vey!
