44KG-IYAgxuPpDCIGexMiw.text: Yummy big, ole burrito. Very flavorful. The location was somewhat dreary and dark. I expected a bit more pizazz from such an esteemed restaurant in the vegan community. Overall, I was very happy with the food and service. :)

Tb6L4MxDiArRCXtqQDHstg.text: This is a gem in Phoenix if you like sweets, are vegan, or both. I plan to come here on every visit to Phoenix. Mmmmm I wish I could eat their cupcakes everyday.

tESQxPIym_b94Furj-JYCg.text: While visiting Phoenix my nonvegan boyfriend and I (a vegan) ate here. We tried the banana cream icecream. It was so amazing we rushed back the next day before flying out. If only one of these was near my town!! Loved it! The vanilla wafers just melt in your mouth. So good!!

NJL21BSJbdwtzlIxOf5kfA.text: Nami's brunch on Sunday and breakfast all other days are the bomb. I love their Acai and Quiche during the week. Sunday brunch is a completely different menu and always has a special. All I can say is Nami is a special place.

pJYHw9rRAL1bpekJDg7EEA.text: Came here with some friends, the staff was all really nice, super cool hip spot with awesome vegan stuff, definitely coming back!

5iUWjz8tCLuLwXE2PrDdJQ.text: My wife and I ate here for the first time on 5-3-17.  We shared the Conethugs and Carmony shake.  Weird name but omg, it was so good.  It's a special not always on the menu.  I wish it was but that will just give us a reason to try other things.  The place is very cozy but small inside.  The staff was very friendly, helpful with recommendations and it was very busy.  The parking is limited as they share spots with their other restaurant Green which we haven't tried yet but can't wait.

aVkgt6vlWWJeuhYSAQAApg.text: Nami provided a fabulous sweet ending to a recent date night with my husband... We were full from dinner at nearby Oven + Vine, but wanted a little something sweet, so to Nami we went.  I'd been hearing from about tSoynamis for years, but since I'm not Vegan and don't live or work in the area, I never made it a priority to go.  That being said, our tSoynami definitely lived up to it's expectations...   Since we wanted to share, the first step was agreeing on one of the 20+ flavors.  I didn't want anything chocolate based, and my husband is very particular, so this was quite a challenge.  I narrowed it down to Fluffernutterin, Chai Tiramisu, O', Soy Capitan, and Ginger Snap!  Jared chose the Chai Tiramisu from there.    Made from organic chai, organic animal crackers, soy whip and Nami's house-made organic soy based "tsoft tserve" ice cream, it was a hit, even considering the ten minute wait after we ordered.  (This is one popular spot!)  We finished the entire thing and agreed that it was $4.50 that was well worth it!  I didn't realize that Nami also offers breakfast, coffee, and all kinds of vegan treats in addition to their famous tSoynamis.  Vegan or not, this place is worth a visit... and I'll look forward to returning soon.

40LMD-ImYpj2Lg6bfornbA.text: The paradise! You can indulge yourself with so many things... I've been there at least 10 times since i moved to Phoenix (4 months ago eheehe)  The samoan cake is beyond delicius, hot latte with almond milk is really heavenly and for the ice creams... well i have difficulties to name the best because are so tasty all of them... (and I didn't try them all yet, they have such a big selection!!)  vanilla shake and mint syroup... OMG!  This is the Paradise, believe me.  ps. for the parking you can easily put your car on the other side of the road, is exactly in front of Nami... =) plenty of parking spots !

VvcMEP6h5z-5DX26FZTx-g.text: We don't deserve Nami. It's perfect. Part of what makes it so awesome is that they don't always have the same pastries/donuts and you're always wondering what the brunch special is going to be this week.   If you haven't been here and you're vegan, you need to go. Stop reading this and go. I won't be offended. This is the best vegan joint in the world in my opinion.   The Rodney Dangerfield (donut sand which) special is definitely what I would choose as a last meal. There's a great selection of breakfast and brunch on the regular menus but it's all about the specials.   They also have tsoynamis, just like their sister restaurant, green. Real awesome for a hot day. There's parking around even if not in the lot, so don't worry about that.   The service is amazing. All of the staff are super cool and friendly and they might even refer to you by name. Ooooor I've just had way to many of their donuts. Could be one or the other.   I moved away from AZ last month and I definitely miss Nami more than I miss some people out there.

NgEb7jvtCHOhO2U7A6ayQA.text: Stopped in while visiting from out of town and enjoyed the cactus haboob (tee-hee) w/ hazelnut milk, a cinnamon concha, red velvet cupcake, and coffee w/ house creamer. The haboob had that "hippy" taste to it if u know what I mean...earthy (but was cinnamon-y sweet and good). They only do double or quad shots so go big or go...double. The concha was the highlight for me, crumbly-sweet cinnamon magic encrusted upon a soft and doughy roll.  Service was good and we enjoyed our treats while sitting outside by gently-swaying vines.  Parking is a mess-nightmare, be exxxtra careful.

4Y0zkEAzRUtxsjpoQgvMFg.text: Stopped in for a fine baked good! We were setting out for the drive back to LA and hit the vegan sandwich shop next door for the road and decided to get a big smore thing here at Nami for desert. Might as well eat well on that long drive home. Their other pastries and deserts looked scrumptious and i will totally come back for more next time i am in Phoenix. Highly recommend.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

fWDCMBRvIzSsQC5PTpxRrQ.text: I have been dying to stop here and check it out and today was the day. My sons girlfriend and I made a trip for some breakfast and coffee. Just off the freeway and an easy place to spot with the bright teal building and signs pointing the way. The location is small, but has quite a bit of parking. There is a handful of seating inside as well at patio seating. We picked up a few menus from the counter and decided on an acai bowl, vegan biscuits and gravy, a cold brew with almond milk and sf vanilla, as well as an iced caramel mockiato. We only had to wait in line for a few moments because someone was in front of us. But were able to reach the counter pretty quick. We were given a number and everything brought of to us when it was ready. Everything was so delicious. Fruit was fresh and granola tasty and just enough crunch. My cold brew was my favorite and probably the best I've ever had. It was over powering or weak just perfect. Great flavor. I wish it was closer so I could get it more often. My sons girlfriend really enjoyed her biscuits and gravy and said her coffee was awesome like mine. I can't wait to go back and try and the desserts because we were way too full when we were done today.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Acai bowl
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Cold brew with almond milk and sugar free vanilla

Neqy6GSKo7SuV5WRomj7QQ.text: They have really tasty soft serve. Some days their customer service is off but every time Rachel is there our order comes out perfect. Overall I've had good experiences here but it does seem like there's a lot of workers in the back and they do at time ignore the customers and are more concerned with chatting amongst themselves. I will keep coming here for the soft serve and blended soft serve creations.

U1JGenlvAml5QMflPBlMmA.text: We are a dairy and gluten free family, so finding treats for special occasions was sometimes a challenge. Not anymore, thanks to discovering Nami! The dairy free tSoynami Sundae concept is brilliant, and there is a combination of tsoft tserve flavors for everyone! My little sister loves the vanilla cookies and cream and that's what she ordered today, but there are so many other delicious favorites, I don't think I've ever tried one that I didn't like! The baked goods are also delicious, and their coffee is bomb! I tried the Cactus Haboob today, and not only is the name hilarious and Arizona appropriate, but the latte is also agave sweetened (a huge plus!) and perfectly cinnamon-y! Can't wait for our next sweet visit to Nami!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

_N-VaZCFihZQZsVESvyltg.text: This was our first stop in Phoenix thanks to other yelp reviews. The inconvenience of arriving at 8:30am but not being able to order Sunday Brunch until 9am was subsided by having coffee and donuts readily available. The vanilla donut + coffee w hazelnut milk was so good! Thankfully we could get back in line to beat the rush of people ordering food for dine-in or takeout. While the service was friendly, it was a little slow. Our tofu scramble, potatoes, and huevos rancheros were  delicious, and their homemade hot sauce was super flavorful and overall our breakfast was very good. I'd recommend skipping the biscuits as they were very small and over cooked. However, we are so thankful for fully vegan restaurants when we travel and would definitely recommend a visit and ordering some pastries to go!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

aTryUag_QFkmqWqgQ_Wvng.text: I cannot express how AMAZING this place is. The food is absolutely amazing. The prices are very reasonable and the staff is always very friendly. I love having a cruelty free "junk food" place that we can take our family to and enjoy a night out. The only thing that would help would be better parking! When they're super busy, finding a parking spot is pretty hard and there is sometimes not enough seating. Just goes to show how amazing this place is though!

gj4FzJPioPbqIEUasG66FA.text: Came here twice for breakfast and once for a treat on our 4 day trip to Phoenix! This place has amazing breakfast and great treats. I had a coffee flavored donut and I am not even vegan my boyfriend is and you would never know the difference the taste was completely on point if not better than a regular donut with actually dairy products. Very pleased and we will be back.

82v05JDMZ_sKpPOH6Mb48A.text: Omg!! If you can't have dairy and need an ice cream like dessert .. run don't walk to this place .. cute little shop with a long list of tsoynami items..   On today's visit I had the life's a peach option with vanilla  soft serve ice cream.. this is a deconstructed peach cobbler in a cup with granola & caramel .. yes please!!   The soft serve ice cream is organic soy & coconut milk tsoft tserve ice cream and is available in chocolate, vanilla or swirl ..   I'll be back to try every flavor on the menu ..   Dessert case had cupcakes, donuts and other yummy looking treats .. vegan friendly!!   Friendly staff .. tip jars ask Sing in the car or Sing in the shower? I voted car!!

-4bPWE5D3t0GMJXQJbZDCg.text: I've been here twice and ordered a few things...  I had a special raspberry mousse parfait thing on my first visit about a month ago and that was amazing!  Today I had a sweet tooth and ordered a cookie dough tsoynami, which is vegan soft serve. It was good, and I didn't feel as bad as if I had regular ice cream ;)   I also ordered 2 cinnamon donut holes (they might have had apple in them?) and those were a bit on the dry side...the maple nut donut, however, was the best of all...very soft and sweet dough!  Good place and it's next to Green's vegetarian which has amazing food...parking is horrible there as it is very compact lot.   Given that this location is rather far from me, I doubt I will visit a lot but I definitely recommend it!

2ENdY2NbOhBMQxp8UunwaA.text: I have never really been a fan of Nami because I have had great Vegan donuts, ice cream, pastries, and other sweet treats from establishments all over the country. Nami just doesn't cut it, to be honest, but I do highly recommend the "Rodney Dangerfield". It is basically a chik'n patty with all the fixings including bacon served on a glazed Vegan donut. b-x9BQkFPOBbKg-Z0uBHIw.text: I am such a huge fan!! I was in Phoenix for three nights.. and I came to Nami three times! If I lived in Phoenix, I would surely be a regular!  I twice stopped in for a tsoynami, which is the vegan answer to a blizzard. I tried the "Betterfinger" one night and the peanut butter and chocolate kind the second. Always they were delicious. I wish more places were doing this soy soft serve!  I also came for breakfast on a Saturday morning. I ordered a bagel sandwich with tofu, tempeh, and vegan cheese. It was really good, and it came with a side of fruit. The only critique would be that it took a really long time. But good things come to those who wait!  I also grabbed an apple fritter for my breakfast the next morning, as I had an early flight to catch and no time to find something vegan to eat downtown or at the airport. Even after surviving the night in my hotel's mini fridge, it was awesome.  Thumbs up all around for Nami!

D5wURgCzDP_JzdNSL3V8Sg.text: I love that places like these give the vegan community a place to indulge and relax. I'm not a huge sweet tooth but I can see how others who do enjoy their desserts find this place fantastic. I like that there is a variety of options for everyone whether it is their baked goods or their tsoynamis. A pastry or ice cream parfait. I love the chill vibes and the fact that I can get a caffinated beverage if I wanted to. It's a judgment free zone that is legitimately good and I would recommend it for a treat. I wish there was a little more seating and that there were more fruit-based options rather than the primarily rich flavors, but otherwise a great place to chill after a meal or whenever.

mTL-ltKKUFumW_b50G5nKQ.text: If the restaurant next door has the best vegan food then nami has the best vegan desserts. This place is the.  Its very small with a lot of personality.  Very good menu from coffees to ice cream, donuts and cookie dough. I love vegan ice cream and after lunch i saw nami had soy ice cream and I of course had to try it. I was blown away there ice cream combinations are insanely good and such a treat. The flavors are so good and honestly you cant go wrong with any ice cream creation here you will not be let down I guarantee it. Eating next to the counter I couldn't stop staring at some donuts they had and also I fell for it and glad I did. I had a chai donut and it was also crazy good. This place is good and had so many options for a great dessert. I'm hooked and will make this a regular stop for me

jQapm7Kj-5F6mg4EG8Q92w.text: I went vegan 7 years ago. I have been coming here ever since on a very regular basis and the food is OUT OF THIS WORLD AMAZING! I've had a lot of vegan food over the years from around the valley and it's good, but nothing comes close to Nami.   Also check out Green next door if you are looking for a burger that'll knock your socks off!   Nami is my go to for breakfast and Sunday brunch, Green is my go to for lunch and dinner!(:

DD6OfILEHtDkHp9lRfQyeA.text: WHOA! Damn good ish here let me say let me say!   I looked this place up before I came out to AZ and I was so excited and it matched up to what I thought it would be which was.. AMAZING!  I got 2 Lemon cupcakes that had this amazing frosting on top and inside the cupcakes. I smashed both cupcakes at the airport the next day. They were still amazing the next day and moist!!!!! Ugh so damn good.  I came in when they were closing in a few minutes so they didn't have a lot of anything next. I really wanted one of the tsunami shakes ! Ugh they were out I think but if they weren't I am not sure why I didn't order one! I am going to have to tell my girlfriend to go and order one so I can live through her. I will be back for you tsunami... I will get you inside me...!   For what I had, Nami is boss and they had me at hello. Hopefully we see each other again or I find you somewhere closer to me.

Mn_pV9BNqDX1TvWJ9SN79g.text: I just discovered their AFFOGATO! It's divine! No, really. I have no words for how fantastic it is. I will never sleep again.

YT07S3QSrjoBvxsRdkOBFA.text: Not really into the healthy scene so much but was pleasantly surprised when i tried nami. My family got the chick-o-stick soynami and was delicious.

mo8GBLyFnMWnsmfz46J6Iw.text: I've been here a few times, most recently for brunch! I've been meaning to try their breakfast items considering how much I love their tSoynamis and Green.   The set up is a little confusing. I didn't realize that you have to order at Nami, but have the choice of sitting there or at Green next door. We opted to sit at Green, since there's much more space. One of my friends who is a strict vegan, suggested the biscuits and gravy-and almost everyone in my party ordered it. I haven't had biscuits and gravy since going meat free a few years ago so I was pretty excited about it! I also ordered their pumpkin spice mocha. It tasted like a holiday in a cup. So, so delicious.  Our order arrived not long after we got our table at Green, so service was quite quick! Our food was quite tasty! They have the market cornered on that dish! I can't find another place that has a vegetarian friendly b&g! Even my boyfriend who is a big meat eater thought it tasted good! The scramble was alright, I think I expected it to taste more like eggs than the veggie taco meat that I make at home (we're probably using the same seasonings-who knows!) It was still good, just not what I was expecting. The potatoes were phenom! Perfectly crisp on the outside! Yum.    Looking forward to a return visit! Green and Nami are two of the best vegan spots in the area!

KJfDepRn3J79nzjw2hOrxQ.text: As I never expected a vegan restaurant (Green) to have the best hamburger I've tried, I felt the same about cheesecake. I almost didn't bother ordering it. I mean it's main ingredients are eggs and dairy. But this was delicious! Sweet but not too sweet, rich, creamy.... I've had cupcakes, Tsoynami's, cookies. It's all good. You can't go wrong regardless of what you order. I even had gluten free biscuits and gravy here. Just like mom makes!

hpUEEpi5Pkzbv7EKtcS6Kg.text: I'm not really sure what the big deal is with this place. It's fine but nothing really tastes better than you can get anywhere else... it just costs more.  It's not the kinda place that you want to go and just hang out as there is nowhere comfortable to sit and it's really small.

OjQsRAm7tcXIKYP69bnphg.text: Met 3 friends here for what I thought was supposed to be coffee but turned out it was supposed to be lunch. Fitting that I came in confused, because the menu here is the most confusing I've ever seen. Chalkboard, display items, a few specials hand written on signs, and a print menu hidden behind the cash register so we didn't find it until we had waited in line and tried to make our choices from the scribbled notes. They would do well to have one readily available printed menu with all offerings. So we had 2 GF folks and they got the zebra donut and loved it. I got a bagel with herb cream cheese and it was yum. Later we saw the table next to us eating grits and it looked so good we ordered one to share. Very tasty and filling.

AiMyJyhYGnzbhKoS4zhcSw.text: HORRIBLE service. I cannot believe it. It took a girl 15 minutes to pull a pitcher of coffee out of the refrigerator and put it in a cup. That's all I ordered. An iced coffee to go. I'm never coming back.

8CSWG7NQzXyjG1XMjScWNw.text: I've have used Yelp several times to find great places to eat, but unfortunately my first review is going to have to be negative :(  I visited Nami with a friend the other night and had a pretty bad experience. Basically, the prices were not truthfully stated, the customer service was selective/awful depending on who you are and what you ask, and they seem to be lacking in their regard for those with food allergies.  The long version: It's a cute place and seemed busy with a mostly young, artistic crowd hanging out. After staring at the main menu for a minute trying to figure out where the ice cream was, an employee handed us a separate menu to see the ice cream selection. My friend ordered first, and then I ordered. Everything seemed normal and fine up to this point, but when the cashier told me the price was $5.50 as opposed to the $4.50 listed on the menu, I was a little taken aback ( I hadn't added any toppings) and politely asked why the price jump.   She suddenly became very short with me, almost angry, started handling everything roughly while telling me that there was tax and also that chocolate always cost more (which wasn't previously stated anywhere that I could find). I felt intimidated by her and wanted ice cream, so I said it wasn't a problem and paid. My friend was perplexed at what had just happened and was more angry about the situation than I was at the moment, but I started feeling more annoyed when I turned around to see the same cashier helping the guy behind me and being sweet and flirty with him. Clearly it wasn't just a bad mood that I had accidentally been met with.   When I got my dessert, they called the wrong name (the cashier had never bothered to ask). I was getting sick of everything and thought it would be nice to sit outside, but we had barely taken our seats when a random guy off the street who didn't appear to be a paying customer took the table next to us and proceeded to ask if we minded if he smoked. My friend misheard the question and said it was fine, so he lit up. I realize we were downtown and you can only control your patios so much, but I was over it and motioned for us to leave.   Finally, I quickly noticed I was having a mild allergic reaction. I am moderately allergic to peanuts (more akin to food poisoning than anaphylactic shock), and this was the sensation I get when I've eaten a small amount. I had worried earlier that the mixing bowls might not be cleaned adequately between batches, and it seemed my fears were realized. Both my friend and I decided we won't be visiting there again.

5e5ZD7G_rVnzqCz1wd_R0w.text: So adorable and delicious treats! I am not a vegan but the tsoynami is delicious. Great customer service and great atmosphere :)

CUQ3aNm7kmDl3rWry3E29A.text: I have suffered with Celiacs Disease for the last year. So it makes perfect sense to price gouge those in need, right?  $3.75 for one (1) gluten-free cookie. 'Nuff said.  Shame on you.

IQXIUSpk5-vZjWveU4qAlQ.text: I'm not a vegan, I'm not a vegetarian. Who am I kidding, I go to filibertos five times a week and eat chicken nuggets every minute. I tend to stay away from vegan/vegetarian food because its fake - meat like items and that makes me even more nervous than whatever saw dust that's in my chicken nuggets. HOWEVER, nami is GREAT. All their food was delicious and the BLIZZARD. DEAR GOD, THE BLIZZARD/ICECREAM.  As a self-certified icecream expert, this is hands down, the best ice cream I have ever had in my entire life. That includes my travels in other countries, through different states, and raiding the entire freezer section of my local Fry's. The taste is great, the price is great, the texture is - wow, the texture is fantastic. I had my doubts but it was delicious.  If it was closer to me I would buy it every day.

VhNc_p3oGHg1gsUNXxCEXg.text: Ok, I have to admit I haven't been here as much as I have gone to Green in Tempe/Scottsdale but I really which I could come here more.   The desserts are AMAZING and thank God, vegan! I forgot the name of the ice cream I got... coco coffee? It is coffee flavored ice cream with coco puffs in it. OMG so freaking good. The cupcakes here are a bit pricey for what you get. The oatmeal cookie with the creme in between in so good. It isn't overly sweet and it tastes healthy even though it has sugar in it.   Took my non vegan friends here and they loved the captain crunch ice cream (forgot what else was in it). I wish the inside of this place was bigger but you could always go next door to green I'm sure.

eiU8HhvQS2lFCRgltH0O-w.text: Name has the dankest soft-serve soy ice cream! Sometimes there is a long wait for a Tsoynami, but it is worth it!

kAxzjEy_v0fsGRE5I87wmw.text: Tried it out for the first time today and I'm in love! It's a very hipster place, very nice atmosphere. I got the iced cactus haboob which is a latte infused with cinnamon and agave syrup. It tasted amazing! And it's vegan?! It was $4.50 for a 16 oz, so a little pricy, but then again everything vegan is normally more expensive so I'm not complaining about the price. I didn't try any of their pastries, but they all looked very delicious. Only bad thing about this place was the parking. There's very limited parking, and it's shared with another vegan restaurant next door. I went during lunch hour, so parking was full. I had to park at a restaurant close to it. Besides the parking situation, the rest of my experience was amazing! Definitely going back

0n9AHg6Qn-eXbl_Upugikw.text: I'm not sure if I came in on a bad day, but we had horrible customer service from everyone who helped us except for the wonderfully kind guy on register this morning. I'm a vegan who lives in the area and was really excited to finally try this place, and I'm pretty disappointed that I didn't get the same cheerful service so many glowing reviews have mentioned. Having never been there before, we didn't know exactly how the service works, so when we'd received our entire order (including my coffee) but not my boyfriend's drink, we waited 5 minutes and then politely mentioned to a server that we were missing it. She literally said "okay?" (note the question mark) as she rolled her eyes and then never came back. My boyfriend and I just sort of stared at each other awestruck by how rude she was to us, and worst of all I think she may have been an owner or in management. As far as the food went, everything was really good! The biscuits and gravy were our mutual favorite, and everything came out of the kitchen so quickly that it made up for the 15 minutes we waited in line to order. I'm a coffee freak, and their cold brew was perfect. I wanted a to-go box for my donut and was too scared to ask for fear of being snapped at again by someone who clearly feels it isn't their job to help.. Overall, I do recommend this place to vegans and carnists alike, but with caution; expect yummy food but don't expect to be greeted when you walk in and don't expect to see any smiles.

p_t4RQ1MtS_pE_hTlR3rXQ.text: This place is awesome. The acai and Pitaya bowls are super tasty. They have great coffee and the perfect thing to pair with good coffee are their amazing vegan doughnuts. I haven't tried anything on the menu that I didn't like. So excited to have this Vegan jewel in my hood. Everyone that works here is friendly and fun!!

qNPA2iC6DMACVgWHoFijYg.text: While you can find some of my favorites added to my post for Green I just tried an affogoto and I am hooked. I LOVE straight espresso so found myself eating spoon fulls of it straight but by the time i got to the bottom of my cup all that was left was tons of syrup. Next time I'll mix it all up and make myself a vegan flurry for sure.   My friend Mariah works in here, if you see her or any of the staff you'll be greeted with a smile and the owners the man too.   Definitely come in here for some vegan deliciousness but be ready for the post soy gas as well.   Suggestions include peanutbutter chocolate bars, peanut butter frosted banana muffins, tsoynamis, and as stated above AFFOGOTOS!   Oh one more tip, if you like chai get their desert haboob ;)

I9KUig5_M9iKKiXe9YbO6w.text: I am simply in love with their Soynami.  Love Love Love.  Wish there was one near my home so that I can get a Coffee, Coco, Loco.  I dream of them.  I highly recommend them to my healthy and my not so healthy friends.  The best.

vbRHKAm6S0Tv2HpynRozbw.text: The tsoynami was okay, but seemed overpriced for essentially the equivalent of your local DQ treat. Didn't try the coffee. The actually space is very small and not much of a coffee shop vibe (would not recommend for studying).

AfZnxYEpVlr6O_Lri8eQgw.text: Employees that worked on 06/03/18 night shift were extremely rude. ( Alex, Jocelyn.)   Usually the service here is decent it always seems like the employees working behind the counter don't want to be there. I feel as though customer service should be the employees number one priority besides not burning the establishment down and providing decent desserts.   It would have been nice to enter the building and been greeted, because we never are... which is weird. It must not be a company expectation to greet paying customers when they walk in.   The reason why the misunderstanding began was because the vanilla vegan ice cream machine was broken and they wanted to charge extra for the chocolate vegan ice cream. Which doesn't seem justifiable if the machine is down and it isn't the customers fault? I mean it's only 0.50 extra per each ice cream serving, but again I drove 15 minutes to Nami only for the vegan vanilla ice cream.   I must admit the vegan ice cream here is amazing! It's definitely not worth the argumentative sass that the girls tonight gave my boyfriend and I.   I myself work in customer service and respect everyone that enters my employers office with a smile and "Welcome in". I wouldn't expect this place to last as long as they'd hope if the employees treat the customers with such insignificance.

Do yourself a favor and head over to Loving Hut if you want good and healthy vegan food. k0iQ_YDV9SynRGZXGjv8qg.text: Basis for my starred ratings (which skews heavily to the food or drink): 1 star:  Never again. 2 stars:  Poor food, poor experience, extraordinary measures in order for me to come back. 3 stars:  Average, nothing really special, nothing particularly bad. 4 stars:  Very good, would definitely return. 5 stars:  A favorite, one of the best.  Upgraded my rating from the last review.  Remember that this place doe snot serve ice cream.  It's only 50% of what ice cream should be.  Vegan, so no cream, no eggs.  So make that 1/3 of what ice cream should be.  Tried a new flavor of tsoynami today - the chai tiramisu with vanilla "ice cream."  It was pretty darn good.  The coconut flavor (ostensible from the use of coconut oil) still came through, but so did the chai.  The ladyfingers were replaced with animal crackers that added necessary texture.  I've grown a little more enamored with this place and given how good this one tasted, upgrading to 4 stars.  Parking still really sucks.

2NPIlikVTq5quoePmVZZ4A.text: This place is always my number 1 recommendation for brunch/breakfast in the Phoenix area. eFHEgLnwUibKdhbftJH1LA.text: As a vegan new to Phoenix, I was super excited to try Nami for Sunday brunch and some yummy baked goods. Nami definitely didn't disappoint and I'll be back often to indulge in some decadent breakfast pastries and desserts. Bonus: Nami is not only 100% vegan, there are multiple gluten-free options.  The restaurant itself is quite small with limited seating, so you may have to wait a bit for a spot to open up. The good news is that people seem to move through quickly, so despite the crowds I have been able to find a spot on both of my visits. I wouldn't say the ambiance is anything spectacular, but that's ok since the food speaks for itself.   I had a gluten-free blueberry donut and huevos rancheros on my first visit. Both were really good and I was impressed by the gluten-free donut since most are pretty similar to regular cake and not very donut-like. This donut was amazingly close to an old-fashioned cake donut and was the best I've had so far. My omnivore boyfriend said he enjoyed his food and would come back, although I'm guessing that was because he saw how happy I was and not that he was blown away by the food and it's ability to replicate an animal-based breakfast.  On my second visit, I decided to try the betterfinger Tsoynami special (made with chick-o-sticks and chocolate chips). It was really good and the portion was gigantic. I honestly wish there was a smaller size offered; I don't think I could finish one again as it's quite filling. I took a strawberry gluten-free donut and Yankee Doodle snickerdoodle cookie sandwich to go and am excited to enjoy those tomorrow.

kmI7Mu8IG83BY2yqMSL-2g.text: Cutest little shop in cenpho! Stopped by for a quick coffee and donut.   I ordered the infamous cactus haboob which by the way taste amazing! It's like the perfect iced coffee concoction!  I also got the raspberry chocolate donut. And it was good for being a vegan donut. However, a little too bready? If that's even a word. It was literally like a fried piece of bread with icing. Next time I will try a different donut. If you're looking for an airy donut definitely don't get this one. It was yummy overall.   Their menu is pretty to the point they have their espresso, coffees, iced coffees, and their signature drinks. They also do brunch and all sorts of other yummy meals which I will try next time!  Customer service was great cashier was very friendly.  The location is very small and parking is very limited I got there early in the mining so it wasn't too bad, but I feel if it were lunch time I might of been a little hectic.  Definite must try!

AtMu1iC0Tfbdpvhq5tahaw.text: #vegan AMAZING. I was only in town visiting for 2 days and ended up coming here 4 times! It is a cute little spot with limited parking. All the staff I met were splendid and helpful in helping me decode between all the 100% vegan options. There is some cozy seating inside with a few spots outdoors. Go morning and evening to see a lovely transformation with more to eat!  Day 1 Bfast got the nami mcbagel (so flippin good!), a donut (they offer real and cake, both yum), a chocolate milkshake (it was ok  prefer more chocolate) and biscuits and gravy (definitely good, biscuits a little tough, would try again).  Afternoon got soft serve chocolate icecream with chocolate and peanut butter. Way good! Soft serve is tricky to find for vegans. They do vanilla, choc or swirl and then have a TON of fun flavor options to make a lovely dessert.  Day 2  Bfast... so I had to go back for the bagel again!! Toasted bagel with slice of seasoned tofu, tempeh (perfection, and Im usually not a big fan but this was wow), and sauce. Also got a mocha which was alright. And.... went back for more ice cream before leaving the state.  Highly recommend this little spot!

EMeABn62iwltDwPpdzN7hQ.text: We have been coming to Nami for quite some time now and thoroughly love it.  I figured it was time to write a review. I always get the peanut butter chocolate tsoynami, which I love.   Last night, I ordered a kitty ditty with chocolate ice cream and it is my new favorite.  It was awesome!   Also, the truffles are great!

jUFBd64uRnuol8EHVlHqJw.text: It's definitely a treat.  I got to split one with a friend after eating at Green and it was excellent.  A nice alternative for avoiding dairy.  Not sure of the flavor, but pretty sure it had bananas and cookies.  One is more than enough to share with multiple people especially after a meal.  Another great place in the central corridor

t2cs3Fe1j6EFKsQdHmruhw.text: Such yummy vegan treats. Great to have a place where you can order anything and its vegan. The cupcakes are great. Someone bought me a dozen for my birthday and everyone loved them, even the meat eaters. There's one that looks and tastes like a hoho. If your lucky enough to see one in the case, get it. The soynami is out of this world. Think of a dairy queen blizzard made with soy milk and no chemical junk. Soooooo good. Prepare to wait and to stand in line. It's a popular place and some things e made to order. It's worth it.

66yWLCMb-5JxGq1qgkX9xA.text: Good burritos, good coffee and bomb donuts. The wait was a little bit longer than anticipated,but nonetheless great place to stop.  We will definitely be stopping by again when we're traveling through Phoenix!

LNrxSk-EuU7PhPkS8R-HRw.text: OMG is what you will say when you taste their yummy nami!! Phenomenal and amazing!! I've had it all at this place, my favorite go to for large portions and variety of flavors

-p_RWGpGCXvwuaPAgLqJNA.text: After going to Greens scooted next door for some AMAZING baked goods.  DELICIOUS!!!  Hard to believe it is all vegan!  Lemon cupcakes are the best!!!  Everyone enjoyed the soynamis too!!

55oVDZ_ExmQE3D4ArxNtNA.text: Probably the best breakfast burrito I've ever had. And one of the best chocolate cakes I've ever had. Meat eaters will like the sweets and the other food too. Their coffee looked interesting and unique. Great service from everyone. All vegan.

x5u_J-_ZnZt5D4uh2NeuCQ.text: I'm not a vegan, but I went with a vegan friend to Nami. Boy was it delicious! I had their quiche, and I have to say it was the best quiche I've ever had.

2s20mXNeW8TmA305wKlYOg.text: Mine eyes hath seen the glory of this vegan bakery, It indulges my most tender taste buds decadently, If I lived a mile closer, I'd have a huge belly, My mouth is munching on!!!!!!  10 stars. I may have a small sense of patriotism towards the Green/Nami powerhouse being vegan, but there are no reasons to take away stars. More like lots of reasons to add stars. The interior at Nami is small, quaint and humble. It overflows with hipsters and yuppies alike not to mention hard rockers and tree huggers. Everyone who is anyone can find something delicious here regardless of the wear and tear of your converse shoes or how long you've been working on your sleeve. If you have the ability to raise a hand to your mouth carrying a donut, you'll leave happy.  We came for Sunday brunch and were filled with too many "mmmmm"s to count. The tofu scramble was perfection and those wings are seriously wing-ding-dang good. The bevvies are delicious and it's probably doesn't even need to be mentioned that the tsoynamis are the best and surest way to fight the 105 degrees outside. Can't wait to come back and get my birthday cupcake here.

acEROEjKuMOZKj3U7IouKw.text: I was in Phoenix for work recently.  After picking up my rental car, I was in dire need for coffee.  I did a quick yelp search and decided to check out Nami, as it was somewhat on the route to my destination.  The barista greeted me when I walked in and was very friendly when letting me know all the milk alternative options.  I decided to be slightly adventurous and try coconut milk with my latte.  I'm not sure if I particularly liked coconut milk, but it was worth a try.  It was very hot and toasty in Phoenix and I ordered a hot coffee instead of an iced coffee.  Not sure why I didn't think to order an iced one...  despite the hot coffee on a very hot day, I still enjoyed it.  Thank Nami for providing me with caffeine :)

F0OMzEtxcEOl-uwQ3KtBvw.text: The service I received here was very cold and unfriendly. I will never come back here again.   My girlfriend and I came by here to get lunch at Green on Sunday 3-23-14 around 1:45ish. We went into green and asked if they were open. They said "not for another 15 minutes but food was ordered next door."  Ok no biggie. A sign would have been nice but whatever. We went to Nami where the person at the register (I really wish I got her name) gave me the worst experience. I was trying to find a lunch menu but was told "We are serving brunch right now but only for another 10 minutes." When I asked what they served in 10 minutes she said in an unfriendly tone, "we stop serving brunch. We are a coffee shop not a restaurant."   After that we decided to leave and went across the street to Coronado cafe where we had a much better experience. (I will post a different review on that)  I'm not sure if all of their employees have this same attitude to would-be first time customers but customer service to me is very important for first impressions.   This does make me sad since I was looking forward to trying something new.

UPQe-HYp2QDj4muyvM3GPg.text: Nami is great.  I went there twice during a recent trip to Arizona and would have returned if I was there longer.  It was so difficult to decide which tsoynami to order, as they all sounded amazing.  I ended up trying the Rocky Road and the Fluffernutterin'.  Both were delicious.  My only (small) complaint was that the soft serve was a bit icy.  I also tried a couple of their baked good (wish I could have tried more) and was very happy with both - the cookie dough cupcake and the cookie layer cake.  Both were moist and chocolatey with amazing frosting.  If you are vegan in the Phoenix area, go to Nami!

lA2P282iIYyOLXFzhC71FQ.text: I LOVE the product, but it takes so long to get your order that I've been late getting back to work.

Gmf6hruRF8_paSZvbTCDcg.text: I stop by Nami every single time I eat at Green next door. I have had about 5 of their baked goods. My favorite is the Lavender Cookies (light and yummy!) and my second favorite is their Pumpkin Pie (flaky and just enough sweetness).   The ones I didn't like was the white chocolate Gluten Free Cookies because they were super hard and too sweet. The compost bar was suuuuuuper sweet. If you like sweet, than I recommend these, but it was too sweet for me.   Of course the Tsoynami(s) are crazy good. Surprisingly, the peanut butter/chocolate is simple, but delish! I love the Almond Quixote! They are kind of big for me, so I always share with a friend.   The most exciting part is that EVERYTHING is VEGAN! That is the best part since I am vegan. I am so happy that they opened this in Phoenix.   The decor is super modern and neat. I love chillin' with my friends and hanging out here. I am going again soon!

biZfkkddq7AJ_wJAPbjzZw.text: YUM! YUM! YUM! Amazing healthy choices for those that care. Rare selections of ice cream, fro-yo, coffee, teas, and more. A True treat! Enjoy.

cFmYWqBcBu2OZLyBa__M7A.text: I didn't realize that Nami is the coffeehouse arm of Green. I came for breakfast (okay it might have been more like lunch) and was overwhelmed with the choice of baked goods. I got a pour over coffee (which I wasn't all that wowed by, but it was good), the huevos rancheros, and a blueberry fritter.   I definitely didn't need all that food but I had to try it all. The blueberry fritter was awesome. Nami definitely does a great job with their vegan baked goods. The vegan huevos rancheros was an interesting take on the classic dish. It had hash browns, chili-spiced black beans, tofu, and some kind of mystery bean or protein that I couldn't figure out what it was.  Nevertheless it was all pretty good. Not to mention, the place was packed, which is always a good sign. However, don't go there on a weekend expecting to get a seat. Very limited seating and for all the people there, it was a slim chance. Especially with loners like me taking up a whole table.

Jgr00etaJTMlhSN7JvX51g.text: I had thee best vegan chocolate chip cookie dough icecream here!! The atmosphere is a unique mix of hip and relaxation. The staff is really friendly and I cant wait to go there again!

cA7XCepkVG34WLZpWJNrZg.text: Okay, so as a meat eater I came with a TOTALLY open mind having ADORED Green off of Scottsdale Rd. I guess I was expecting a restaurant, but this is DEFINITELY more like a coffee shop or a much much worse version of Lux. My girls and I went for brunch and were very excited, unfortunately the food was NOWHERE near the caliber of what is served at Green.   My girls had some parfait thing, and a donut while I had a bagel with cream cheese and an Italian soda. My bagel and cream cheese were tasty but ABSOLUTELY bland, no chives, no onion, no nothing to spice this bad boy up. My girls said the donut was dry and revolting and the parfait was nothing she couldn't make at home with yoplait and some granola. I have been WAITING to go here with my boyfriend and decided for a sneak peak and I'm glad my boyfriend didn't come because he would have been SO disappointed. For now, only Green is on the radar. It got two stars because the girl taking our order was very gracious and sweet.  We promptly finished our food and then drove over to America's for street tacos and Vampiro's. Sorry Nami.

khMp56hKN2DmUgDNUMxuGQ.text: I usually don't review places that I have only been to once, but I had such a bizarrely mixed experience at Nami that I just had to speak up.   We decided on Nami after reading great reviews of brunch on Yelp.    I hate it when you walk into a restaurant and it isn't immediately obvious what you're supposed to do: sit down? Wait to be seated? Order at the counter? Well this was one of those places, so we did what everyone else was doing and got on line at the counter.   There was almost no evidence of a brunch. No one was eating brunch. The kitchen didn't look big enough to produce brunch foods. There were no obvious brunch menus. Just one hand lettered sign about a brunch special.  My husband wanted to walk out, but I said no, I saw the brunch on their website, lets wait and see what they say.   So we finally get to the front of the line and ask about brunch. The girl at the counter says "yes, we are serving brunch, there should be some menus on the tables." And she sends us over to the seating area.   We went and found menus on one of the tables and realized there was no table service. We got BACK on the line, which was now pretty long. We waited. I ordered and paid. Tables were filling up quick.  We got the last two-top in the small dining room. Whew.   As soon as we sat down, I realized I was so flustered from the menu experience that I'd forgotten to order a side of sage sausage hash. So I got back on line AGAIN.  I noticed another waitress handing brunch menus to the people behind me in line. Which really, really annoyed me. Right after that I learned that the young lady who originally helped us was a trainee, which explains the menu fiasco, but doesn't excuse her lack of common sense.   By the time I finished ordering again and paying again, I had just enough time to grab two free cups of citrus infused water and get back to our table before the food came out. Wow, quick! Except that we only got one of the two coffees we ordered, and it was in a to-go cup (why? Aren't you guys trying to keep stuff out of landfills?)  So here is the good part of my review. The food was really interesting. We ordered huevos rancheros and chilaquiles. The tofu scramble was one of the best I've had. The chilaquiles were a unique presentation in the form of a "cake", kind of like a mille-feuilles pastry.  The posole was addictively good. And when we finally got the sage sausage "hashsheesh", it too was vibrantly flavorful. My only complaint with the food is that a few items were kind of dry (chilaquiles, hash) and could have used more of the sauce, sour cream, etc.  that came with them.   My long-awaited coffee arrived scaldingly hot, with unpleasant looking curdled soymilk floating in it. I remember having curdling issues with soymilk and hot coffee when I first went vegan back in the 1980s, but it hasn't happened to me in a long time.  Meanwhile, my husband's coffee with soymilk was just fine. So I asked one of the waitresses if it was "normal" and after some  discussion of how it should go away if I stirred it (it didn't), she offered to bring another one with steamed soymilk.  Kind of a surprise after being sent to get my own menu and losing my place in line, but I wasn't complaining!   My husband ordered another entree, because he is shameless, so we got to experience the Benedict Arnold, which came along with my new coffee. Again in a takeout cup? (Why? I don't know why!)  More surprisingly vivid flavors from the Canadian bacon and the vegan hollandaise sauce, which was on the thin side but very tasty. And this time, HE got to wait in line to order and pay (folks, if you're counting, that's four waits in line just to have brunch.)  By the time we finished the last bite of tofu scramble, my coffee was still undrinkably hot and we were not at all in a mood to wait on line a fifth time for a pastry or a tsoynami to go.  So there you go: a mixed review. Very good food, but in an atmosphere that made me feel uncomfortable and stressed instead of relaxed and happy. Pretty much the opposite of the "mini-celebration" brunch experience described on the website. If Nami switched to table service and one bill at the end instead of counter service, I would be there every weekend (if I lived in Phoenix...)

_Hc7fdm16xdaKwagYVfEZg.text: Wow their soynamis are amazing . Seriously can't tell it's vegan at all, so rich with flavors ! I had their carrot cake one pmg omg perfect mix of cake soy nami and white choco.    I'm not vegan but have friend and family with lactose allergy and gluetin allergy , but their selections of baked goods are fantastic as well.     I wish I can make it myself.  Tried their lactose free gluten free cheese cake and was fantAstic. Wow definitely my new fav. Spot is so cute, artsy and warm green feel.  Next time I'm going to try their pumpkin soynami and their breakfasts, I'm sure they will be great.     Service was awesome, friendly and knowledgable about ingredients :).   5 stars!

mAVt04crKyJlVG242xaQnw.text: I absolutely love nami! they offer so many so many vegan options which is great if you're like me and you can't eat dairy ;) I especially love their vegan donuts, and they always have new flavors to try. be warned though: they're not like krispy kremes or other regular donuts, because they are vegan, they are much more dense, and coupled with the fact that they are pretty large to begin with, you fill up rather quickly. so you don't need to buy more than one... or maybe two ;) the only downside to this place is that it's very laid back so there's really no sense of urgency in the employees, making time an issue. for example, it took 20 minutes for them to toast a bagel.. that being said this place is still the vegetarian cat's pajamas.

YL6ushU1g3fR3T4lak0ntg.text: I can't believe this place has become this way.  I have been coming here for years and it used to be enjoyable.  Over the last two month's I have come here 3 times and every time I come here there are some super young kids that are working that literally always have the dirtiest judgemental looks on their faces it's very unpleasant when you go to order and people are not even looking you in the eye when they take your money.  And not only have they reduced the cup size of the soy nami by like 40%, they also haven't filled it each time I have come, there has been about 25% missing the first two times and literally half of the cup was empty tonight.. HALF!  But I didn't even bother to say anything because the line was long from them just horsing around the whole time.  I saw some people they seemed to know (?) walk in and they all literally just chatted at the register for a good 10 min, just laughing and joking around.  The people in line were just staring impatiently and the kid says "oh, we will be with you soon.." I couldn't believe it.  I get it you want to have fun where you work, I am an advocate for that we spend 80% of our lives working so we need to make it fun, but you are also running a business and you have lost mine.  It's all just about the money now I guess.

Bo34BBAlYenzDl8l7UDN3w.text: The long awaited, much anticipated CenPho brother to Green is HERE!   While this isn't another Green location (don't worry! they will open soon!), Nami serves a huge menu of their delicious tsoynamis and a variety of other baked goods.  This little cafe is all vegan, and while my vegetarian diet allows me to overindulge in regular ice cream -  these tsoynamis could convert me. I had a flufflernutter (note: NOT a sexual term, but instead a mixture of peanut butter and marshmallow cream) tsoynami that was heavenly and huge. YUM!  I did not try any coffee but am very excited to. They offer soy, almond and rice milk - with promises to add more nut varieties soon. Nami offers a beautiful selection of pastries - cupcakes, whoopie pies, cookies.  The staff here was amazingly friendly and welcoming.  I felt like they genuinely cared about my business, as well as any comments or suggestions that we had.      I am glad that I get to be the first review, since I was their FIRST customer. This vegan-niche is much needed in Central Phoenix and I am so stoked for what Nami and Green will bring to it!

XjubA_RwpSxqaT4JnTvMhA.text: I've ordered the tiramasu soft serve twice and it is soooo good.  It does not taste vegan.

ReCDHmmJCI5_uq3MFdcH8g.text: Awesome vegan goodies that taste as good as the "real" (i.e., "conventional") thing.  Service has always been very friendly and the establishment is immaculate.  The tsoynamis (think healthier version of McBlizzards and yes, that is the correct spelling) are so good; on my most recent visit, I got the Dough Boy, which was chock full of chocolate chip cookie dough.  I also bought a maple glazed doughnut (I would eat the glaze by the spoonful!) which was consumed far, far too quickly.  On another recent visit, I enjoyed an oatmeal creme pie (a sandwich cookie with yummy buttercream) and a chocolate cake doughnut.  Everything I've ever had from Nami has been fresh and fantastic.  Bonus: I can tell myself that everything I eat here is healthy and good for you, because VEGAN.  ;)

5w3kt0iaS5ifweyE0sYFhw.text: First of all, the people who work here are great and very welcoming. It's great!  At first I didn't know this place was vegan, and when I found out I was surprised. It's great! I'm vegetarian and try to eat vegan foods as much as possible. I also do not eat gluten, and it's great that they have vegan, and gluten free pastries! As well as vegan and gluten free ice cream.  The price is very reasonably, $5.00 on the dot, for an ice cream. You can even add extra pecans or strawberries, etc., at no extra cost.   I would recommend this place to anyone who wants great ice cream! Vegan, vegetarian, or not, I'm sure everyone will enjoy it.   The decor is nice as well. With local artists selling their artwork. It's very minimalistic. Which is very nice. It goes with the PHX downtown vibe.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. great tip, you can split your order into two to share.

Hv5hB1B38rWtltK4jUORnQ.text: AHHH THE BEST ICE CREAM EVER!! I'm honestly surprised on how it tastes so similar to dairy ice cream. I'm going to make it my goal to taste every tsoynami on the menu

J8bAW2SYC1BNhsUq2J8D8A.text: They're getting sloppy.  While I appreciate the novelty of vegan ice cream (which, most store bought brands are better) with various mix-ins, and vegan baked goods, there is a lot to complain about.  Their facebook touts Hot Fudge Sundays in which affogatos and hot fudge sundaes are $2. We went there and asked for a hot fudge sundae and were met with confusion by the barista who brought over the other girl who explained that they "do not have sundaes but we can put hot fudge on an ice cream cup."   What? Is that not a sundae?! Did you not have this posted on your facebook as a special? They're doing a poor job of making their staff aware.   Additionally, the more I get tsoynamis, the more they're screwed up. They often will leave out ingredients or sometimes change them completely. This is a VERY big deal because I am gluten-intolerant... If I order a GF tsoynami, what is the risk they will add a non-GF ingredient and I won't notice until I ingest a bit?  I don't know... Maybe I am over the novelty, or maybe they're just getting sloppy.

Tc9Zx17nYPxbzFZEI6Skcg.text: Omg, the tsoynami (vegan soft serve ice cream with various toppings) is incredible! Fantastic and friendly service. Right next door to Green.

7qv0bZ0pXbjTM-T25ESd-w.text: I love Nami! I love their breakfast, I love their desserts, I love their coffee!  The only thing that could make Nami better is if they had a location closer to my house. Even if that never happens Ill still make the drive :)

b31fJ11nDwEVTtiubWhd7Q.text: Honestly, I probably love this place too much! After learning of some food intolerance's I was so excited to find a coffee shop/bakery/brunch place so close that I knew wouldn't have dairy, since all the products are vegan, and have a good amount of gluten free options available on top of that! My mom and I are obsessed with any of their chocolate gluten free donuts, their strawberry cheesecake is divine, and the tsoynamis are so amazing and refreeze perfectly! Their coffee is also just as delicious. Their caramel mockiato is my favorite, but now that I have cut back on sugar I always get a cappuccino which is still very yummy (the taste of their coffee/espresso is scrumptious). All the staff are very friendly and the environment is very relaxed and welcoming.

yxqbpE0RBgr5uM6B6iXvlw.text: Pretty new at eating vegan and I've enjoyed looking for different places to eat. Had been looking forward to checking this place out. Walked in and stood there for a couple of minutes. Someone in front of me was being helped, but no one else working there acknowledged me at all. That's awful to not get any customer service at a place that I have been looking forward to going to. I would not recommend anyone to go here and that's just too bad. I wouldn't even give it one star, but I guess I have to.

Qxuhp-k-UDxN7LSy2csdOA.text: Their coffee and donuts are soooo bad, but sooooooo good....

SWZxnt8B2zambnHW7xG5Sw.text: So, it was just okay ice cream. My biggest complaint was not that. It was actually.... the spoons. I don't want rough wood on my tongue. There I said that phrase out loud, and I would actually not eat there again just because of the coarse wooden spoons. I wasn't the only one in our birthday group that made the, It-feels-like-I-just-licked-a-napkin face. In fact, one of the girls' spoon snapped in two while trying to scoop some of the gummy chocolate out of hers. She threw the almost full cup now with splinter sprinkles away. I've had better ice cream at Baskin Robbins and made no spoon induced grimaces while doing it.

v7TmNNJeXEZs4w5UOJ42_Q.text: Oh NAMI!!!   I love you so much!  It's hard to even convey in words how much I love it there. QJh9ytXf6dLbazZp9JL4dw.text: Amazing vegan treats! We got the chocolate strawberry cake, oatmeal creme pie, vanilla ice cream and the soy boy! Soooo good! Highly recommend! Don't miss out on this great place! Visiting from out of town and we are so happy that we found this place!

l-UsVB1eOL9_1XHcTLDddw.text: If you're looking for a vegan, gluten free cake for a special occasion, this place is tops in terms of flavor. I got my husband a peanut butter chocolate cake for his birthday, and it was fantastic. I've never had such a good gluten free cake before. What marred the experience was that my cake was damaged by the cashier when she put the lid down. They took it next door to the bakery to fix it, but it was still visibly damaged. I did contact the store to let them know of the incident, and they gave me a small gift card to make up for it.   I returned a few days later to share some breakfast burritos with my mom and sister. I had heard about the wholly k-aioli on instagram, and I was dying to try it. It ended up being a kale overdose wrapped in a tortilla, but I loved the big ole breakfast burrito that my sister got. She switched me because she's cool like that.   There are many more offerings, especially for brunch, that I have yet to try. Nami/Green knows how to do vegan junk food!

qrrp5eP4qm5P8hjz51K8CQ.text: Best vegan desserts in Arizona . PERIOD !!! From their soy based frozen concoctions called tsoynamis to their vegan pastries, breakfast and coffees!   They make vanilla, chocolate or a swirl of both. My go to ones are chunkey monkey and peanut butter and banana. But wanted to try something different so tonight we tried the pumpkin pie tsoynami and hubby got the banana cream pie tsoynami ( he always get that one but I would prefer it with peanut butter and chocolate) and OMG the pumpkin pie tsoynami is AMAZING..... The pumpkin puree is so good , you can actually taste it....it definitely isnt covered up by all the spices.....just pure pumpkin with vanilla and Graham crackers. YUM.....  Again friendly staff, small seating area but always fortunate to find seating every single time we are here (thank you universe). They too have outdoor seating but their parking can be a bit of a pain.   Go get dinner before hand next door and come here for dessert! You will not regret it....after all peace begins on our plate !

DzwCXs1YmiFN4mPfGQku4Q.text: Great breakfast selection. Ordered tofu egg sandwich and captain crunch donut. I love when they bring old school cereal donuts back. Amazing! Parking is pretty limited, so plan according when you want to stop in. Pet friendly patio.

The place was busy, but staff was fast and friendly. We will definitely be back next time we are in the area!

7jOom6kEMJEdQkj9T4OxtA.text: Based on the reviews, I wanted to like this place. It was a busy Saturday morning and the line was out the door. Nami itself was packed and the cashiers were working as fast as they could. So my group and I decided to try the breakfast spot next door - only to find out they're closed and they help Nami during the weekends. Okay, great. So we'll wait......In the blazing sun, I waited outside as room inside was made available for me to come indoors and actually look at the menu. I was disappointed. Not only with the lack of venue space but the speed of service was slow along with the small sizing of the vegan baked goods. I spent $20 on 3 items and a chai drink. I think that's a bit overpriced, even for a vegan cafe.

eEui53W7Of6QV0OdJls8gg.text: Phoenix Coffee Culture 9/13 -- checking Nami off the list for 9!  This little shop is as unique as it gets and it's Vegan! Before you press "x" or that little circle, give the reviews a little read first. From food, pastries, coffee, tea and other specialty items Nami gives dairy using cafes a run for their money. Their menu is punny and whimsical, which makes this place feel down to earth and enjoyable.   I decided to caffeinate myself with their "Cactus Haboob" a Cinnamon infused Agave Syrup latte (iced) and decided to go with their Maple Bar, that was gluten free. I am not a vegetarian, vegan or have gluten intolerance but I thoroughly enjoyed what I ordered! The latte was perfect, I'm the type of person who craves more cinnamon-spice flavor in my Chai (yes, I am aware it contains more spices than that) which is why I went with the Cactus instead of the Chai Latte. It wasn't overly sweet, caffeinated me well and was delicious -- even with Soy milk. The Maple Bar was a typical fried donut, though not as fluffy, but semi-airy. It was actually impressive, though it was a bit too greasy.  Besides the slight greasy donut (kind of expected), the pricing is a bit steep for what it is. $4.50 for my iced drink and $4.25 for the maple bar, a bit too ridiculous for a GF donut IMO.  Beautiful little space, tons of tables and outdoor seating. The cashiers were informative and answered questions customers had thoroughly. It looks like the Tsoynami's are the most popular thing here, I might have to come back to try it and their food. Great place to catch up with friends, spend solo time or to read. No outlets from what I've seen so far though.

I have a dairy allergy and am pretty use to coffee shops using the cheapest soy milk they can find to pacify us non-dairy people, and then typically charge an extra $.50 for it.   Nami is all vegan.  I was pleasantly surprised when I went there and asked for a  latte and they asked me, "would you like that made with soy, hazelnut, almond, or coconut milk?"  WHAT!?! choices?  They also informed me that once they get more settled they want to start making fresh nut milks.   The hazelnut latte is awesome.  Also, the "Nami Cakes" are soooo good.

eKLRjJ86aMjT07Ul5qN7bA.text: I think ice cream is pretty disastrous, so when I tried the tsoynami, I was in frozen dessert heaven.  I've only tried the fruit blend versions, and crave them regularly.  They're good.  And they're big.  My daughter and I are easily satisfied sharing one.  I'm not a coffee drinker, but do enjoy a good chai latte now and then.  This, by far, is the best chai latte in town.  It's got a fairly descent spice (and I love the spice), and I can actually taste the ginger.  And of course, no dairy.  On the down side, my mom loves her dose of half n half in her coffee.  The non-dairy options just didn't satisfy her one bit.  I would imagine that most of my dairy loving friends might be reluctant to join me there.  Oh well.  P.S. Thanks for the doggie-patio love.  She loves riding over with me.

jkLhY-sx2lTy4KXAp8Herw.text: Stopped in for a quick latte + work session and Nami turned out to be a great choice. Delicious iced latte served up by a friendly team in a cute shop. It seemed as if every other patron was stopping by for some ice-cream-in-a-cup-with-stuff-on-it gloriousness, but I stuck it out with coffee. Sigh. At least the coffee was on point.

KEwJ-PW6bdSfpfcGU7QLwg.text: Items sampled across visits:  Deez Hazelnuts Tsoynami - Hazelnut Brittle, Dark Chocolate Bar, Chocolate Fudge  Pumpkin Pie Tsoynami - Pumpkin Puree, Pumpkin Spice, Vanilla Wafers, Maple Syrup, Whipped Cream  Betterfinger Tsoynami - Chick o Stick, Chocolate Chip, Buttercrunch Syrup  Snicker Fudge  Zucchini Donut  Blueberry Fritter  Blueberry Cream Cheese Turnover  Gluten Free Yankee Doodle  Namicake  Cinnamon Roll  Red Velvet Champagne Cupcake  Coffee  Maple Bar  Nami-o Donut  Chick o Stick Donut  Smiley Face Pancakes  Having admitted my fondness for baked goods and a perhaps odd fascination with vegan pastry it was only a matter of time before I visited nami - in part due to the aforementioned interests and good word of mouth from a vegetarian friend and in part due to its location just down the street - but little did I know just how good it would turn out to be...or how many times I'd visit (Three to be exact, the most recent being a breakfast with friends on 12/30/12.)  Owned by Damon Brasch and operated on a daily basis by what seems to be a collection of cute college girls that you might see at Whole Foods or a local Co-Op, most of the things that nami does it does very well, perhaps most surprisingly their vegan take on the Blizzard entitled 'tsoynami,' the rich soy-based ice cream lacking any hint of "soy" and fixed with any number of mix-ins, some menu staples and other seasonal.  Available 7:00am to 9:30pm I've had them at both ends of the spectrum and honestly prefer them to any frozen "shake" I've had save for, perhaps, the concretes at Shake Shack - the pumpkin was particularly excellent as part of breakfast.  Moving to the baked goods, as much as I wanted to like the donuts I just could not, save for the baked zucchini version and the dense blueberry fritters.  Perhaps it was the glaze or perhaps the actual batter but something about each of them harkened that 'beany' flavor that turns so many off to soy based vegan foods.  More impressive, perhaps due to the intense sweetness or a different glaze, the cinnamon roll was a much better choice, as was the turnover with a light flakey shell, sweet whipped soy, and fresh blueberry puree.  Moving on to the rest - I think it is safe to say that anything nami makes with chocolate is a safe bet - the rich organic tablets behind the bar likely 70% cocoa or better and a dominant flavor whether in a tsoynami, drizzled on a pancake, baked into a moist cupcake, or best of all made into dense "snickers" fudge that trumps the original by miles.  Last, and certainly not least, for those who don't want chocolate - and all the more so for those unfortunate enough to be gluten intolerant (the real sort, not the trendy Hollywood stuff,) get the Yankee Doodle - a nearly quarter pound snicker doodle sandwich with dense, creamy filling, that is better than any snickerdoodle I've had elsewhere - vegan, veg, gluten free, or otherwise.

CcVo3XSssTG3kfF83yc0hw.text: I wouldn't even know where to start with this place. My girlfriend and I visited this place after eating at the American vegetarian next door, which had seemed to be connected to this cafe. There were so many vegan options. They had cookies to cupcakes. Their coffees did not look half bad either. Within the 3 days I spent in Phoenix, I found myself here 3 times as well.  We were so stoked to find vegan biscuits and gravy here. They came with some potato square hash and some tofu scramble which had to be some of the best i have had yet. I also got the country breakfast burrito which was so good as well. The worker was so nice when i had asked for ketchup and had to go in the back to get it for me.  As for desserts, their soynamis were pretty much a soy soft serve. I was not a huge fan of their chocolate one, so I found myself happier when I ordered just the vanilla with my soynamis. Over the course, I tried the cookie dough one (which was a bit sweet when ordered with swirl), the mint one (which was so fun with the vanilla), and the marshmallow one (which was probably my favorite). The workers here were so nice. The place was so nice. I'm kind of glad I don't live in Phoenix. I would be there way too often and would probably give them all of my money.

Fg4RluV7VhaxN6N-dEVJ4g.text: I'm a little disappointed about the changes they've made. I used to live in Central Phoenix very close to nami and enjoyed coming here. I moved to another part of town and don't get a chance to get out to nami as much as I wish I could.   I went this weekend for the first time in probably a year. First the guy behind the counter asked if I wanted chocolate or vanilla. I told him I never had the chocolate since it wasn't an option when I lived nearby. He just said "it's not very good" so I decided against trying it. Then I was sad to see that they reduced the size of the cups but the price didn't change. But THEN they only filled my new little cup about 2/3 the way with product!?! I feel that I got around 1/2 the normal portion I used to get for the same $5. I was happy to see they ditched the weird wooden spoons and got plastic.   Overall I really enjoy this place but feel that they are now overcharging for the portions they are giving. Also some of the "special" flavors on the board haven't changed in 3 years!

8CqIDiUzEZmKJcI_sTBsag.text: I was first referred to Nami (and Green!) when I moved out to Phoenix through a very friendly vegan. Coming from Chicago, I fully expected to find fewer quality vegan options in the city of Phoenix. After my first visit to Nami, I was clearly proven WRONG. From the delicious vegan donuts to the surprisingly tasty orange juice-espresso drink, to the infamous Sunday Nami brunch, I fell in love.   But my favorite part? Their soynami, which is a guilt-free version of a McFlurry; a vegan's dream in a cup of yum. I've even taken my S.O., an avid meat eater, to try their breakfast burritos. It's his new favorite breakfast spot. Vegans and meat eaters alike, rejoice!   The staff is always so friendly and even recognizes their regulars. The owner is a passionate, dedicated vegan man who understands what a passion for animals really is.   If you're looking for a healthy, environmentally-conscious meal that tickles your tastebuds, look no further. Nami is your next stop.

Even so, we ended up getting the yogurt parfait with fresh fruit, the bagel with schmagel and the nami McBagel sandwich. Despite not being vegan eaters (just DF), my husband had the McBagel and we were both very impressed by the herb cream cheese. It's better than any I've tasted or purchased! This isn't much of a restaurant as much as "get it and go" type of place, but we'd definitely come here again. I also enjoyed the cinnamon haboob latte with hazelnut milk!
