zWE-XRREbVr-WMN7rd-tdg.text: We awoke unexpectedly at 5:30am. We tried shutting our eyes, yet we were unable to be greeted by sleep once again. Lethargically lounging around the house as the sun sneakishly peeked through the grayness of densely blanketed sky, we shuffled for thought. Nothing! No Spotify station or Netflix series could keep us bound by confinement. We were insatiable, for............  A MILKSHAKE!!!!!!  Nami was the only place open to satisfy our desires. The menu was appealing. I tend to turn my nose at GF and non-dairy items even though dairy causes some sure unpleasantries.   The place is small and cute. Behind the bar looks like a janitors closet. (I liked it). We felt bad ordering shakes so damn early in the am, but we eradicated the guilt and proceeded. She got the chocolate shake and a cookie dough cupcake. I chose the espresso shake, matcha tea latte doughnut, and also the cookie dough cupcake. Neither of us particularly cared for our shakes despite drinking them in full. It was the doughnut we've been talking about since. The matcha tea glaze that seems to also be supplemented with orgeat, was ok. Interesting, nonetheless. It kind of resembled, faintly, the taste of seaweed, which I don't mind, just unexpected. Still, it was good. However, this doughnut! Effing amazing! It was so perfect. Can you do regular glazed doughnuts in addition to the flavored offerings??? Holy Jeez!!! They'd be sooo good! Thanks!

LGlkqtALpt6XSzPzjx3NAw.text: My first vegan restaurant and the country breakfast burrito was fantastic! The tofu scramble was delicious! Not even a tofu fan but never would've known. Brought my vegan friend from Texas and she loved it. I will definitely go again!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. There delicious treats, had the banana churro, like a donut hole.

WzqYyLeS326V_1sM94M7eg.text: Went here for Sunday brunch and this tiny place was super busy! The line was out the door and wrapped around the building. I had higher hopes for the burrito I ordered but maybe I just need to try something else off the menu. It was kind of bland and the slice of bread in the burrito was an unexpected surprise. I ordered the Benedict expecting it to be oozing with hollandaise sauce and I couldn't see or taste any of it. It was mostly just tofu scramble with a couple pieces of asparagus and potatoes. Their coffee was fantastic though and the rest of the group seemed happy with their meals. The inside is very small and seating is limited so ordering to go is probably a smart idea. For as busy as it was it didn't take long at all for our food to get to the table. All the staff was really friendly and overall it was a really good experience. Next time we're in Phoenix I'm definitely coming back to try their famous ice cream!

ZOvQmSa60RBRj4gqjHrBMA.text: The atmosphere is very young-people-ish in my opinion. When you go in it smells funny. The good things about Nami are that the employees are nice and the strawberry shortcake tsoynami is delicious. As I looked at the wall on my last visit, the drink of the week was pumpkin spice latte. It is a vegan-friendly place.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Strawberry shortcake tsoynami. Real dessert :)

ah4zA_dUiPMfPPpCScxAmw.text: Went here for brunch as the menu items sounded interesting and good. It turned out to be anything BUT good! I'm from the South and I know biscuits .....and they should be arrested for calling the heavy, doughy, strong herb flavored round things on my plate biscuits, yet alone serving them to me! The gravy poured over the top was cold and had no flavor. The tempe bacon came out in a bowl and was nothing but deep fried crumbs, mostly pieces you couldn't even pick up with your fingers.  The hominy grits were described as being in a creamy lemon-garlic sauce....you guessed it....not at all as the menu stated! It was a disgusting pinkish orange colored sauce that tasted very strange and loaded with a sour sriracha flavor. The home fried potatoes were hard & cold and the tofu scramble was cold as well and had no flavor. We also tried a maple flavored donut that also had no flavor - not even a hint of maple - only very greasy. We spent $52.00 for brunch and did not like one thing! If you do decide to eat here - bring some TUMS or a very strong antacid!!!

U9alaZg8iVZQx_CQlrmVoQ.text: I live in Portland, the apparent mecca of all things vegan. Surprisingly, there is one thing we don't have here that Phoenix does: the tsoynami.  "Isn't it just vegan soft serve?" you say. "Anyone can make that. You have that in Portland!"  Um, it's not just vegan soft serve! It's extra thick, extra creamy, not-too-sweet vegan soft serve. And then they put stuff in it! Completely different. It's basically a veganized Blizzard. Not only do they have the classic combinations you remember from the DQ (banana cream pie? with vegan nilla wafers?), but they have their own delightful and creative combinations. I'm kind of embarrassed by how many of these things I've eaten since I've spent a total of maybe three days in Phoenix, but my favorite combination is Cap'n Crunch Berries and strawberries. Maybe you're like me, and somehow the seemingly obvious combination of cereal and ice cream has eluded you until now. Well, go to nami and the nice folks there will set you straight about that.  The only thing I wish they would improve is the whipped cream. If, like me, you are not a fan of coconut, then it tastes overwhelmingly like coconut. I know some people like coconut, or don't think it clashes with whatever dessert they are eating, but I don't think the flavor of coconut belongs in my banana cream pie tsoynami, okay? I know, I sound ungrateful. However, it does not stop me from literally mandating that we stop and get tsoynamis every time we're in Phoenix. It shouldn't stop you, either! Just maybe order something without that.

Xc2QI3ZyWhGnMS3zzXhn9A.text: AMAZING !!!!!!!! I visited from Orange County, CA and i had to make two visits because there is nothing like this back in California!!!!!!!! the soft serve is absolutely delicious! i bought two cupcakes and a cookie for back home but they didn't even last the plane ride  definitely will be visiting phoenix very soon to get my Nami fix !!!!

B2UOUoCwNk8k7lgEa-MjrA.text: Snicker doodle  yummy! Worth the trip to come and tray some desert. If you are a vegan or having a little allergy restriction; come by here! I can't have dairy and this place is my new spot

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

l5SRibXzqkCTrT-61MssIQ.text: This ice cream was bomb, I had the mint with big cookie chunks and it was awesome! The bakery looked good too but I was here for the ice cream.

z7ycxIJ9dc7oeUdsn8JleA.text: I came here when I was in Phoenix after eating at the vegan restaurant next store. They have a large variety of vegan pastries, many of which are gluten free, and vegan ice cream. I got three pastries, the strawberry cupcake (which I believe was gluten free), the yankee doodle (also gluten free I believe) and the chocolate, berry croissant. The strawberry cupcake was okay but the other two were amazing! The cake was kind of dense in the cupcake but I did enjoy the frosting and the fresh strawberry on top. The yankee doodle was 2 snickerdoodle cookies with frosting in the middle. It was amazing, one of the best vegan, gluten-free treats I've had. The cookies were moist and flavorful and the frosting sweet and delicious. The chocolate, berry croissant was excellent too. The croissant itself was good, but not quite as buttery and rich as a non-vegan one. The chocolate was more of a chocolate mousse and had very good texture and wasn't too sweet. It was also topped with some yummy fresh berries. I'm gonna try the ice cream next time I'm in Phoenix.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Yummy, vegan goodies

El9U9kYWnpmKfV7QuFRNog.text: A vegan bakery in Phoenix.  I was so impressed by this place that I have decided to write a separate blog post about it.  I am awestruck that I could get dessert out in a bakery.  It has been so long since I was able to have ice cream out.  Everything in the bakery is vegan including the soft serve ice cream.  I ordered the doughboy vanilla soft serve.  It was amazing my mouth is still watering from it.  Highly recommend.

vyVfk0GVkiTP-kX-3gchqg.text: This place is just good.  I ordered to go coffee and doughnuts for the people helping me move and the doughnuts were gorgeous!  My Polish friend keeps saying "they are like the doughnuts in Poland!' and wants more!  I really want to also go there for brunch/breakfast.

BMPo5bq_BT4TIl5pb7u7pA.text: Sadly their ice cream machine was down the day I visited and they were out of many things, but I knew I couldn't leave without at least trying something! I got a dark chocolate raspberry donut and oh my god was it moist and delicious. I'm not sure if all vegan donuts are just blessed with this ability to be so moist and delicious or I've just been lucky; either way I'm not complaining. I can't wait to go back and actually get a Tsoynami and compare it to J. Selby's Soyclone from home here.

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Dark chocolate raspberry donut

XDHXvETr0p0U7mw4E8-LsQ.text: We've never had ice cream this good, and it's even better knowing that it's not cream! Their "tsoynami" ice cream concoctions are constantly changing, always creative, and totally delicious! They also have great pastries, including Mexican pan dulce vegan style, which is exactly like the non-vegan version of this traditional sweet bread. We can't get enough of this place!

QVK8MDkUBAKuRxt1KU-n2g.text: Happened to be way up in Phoenix proper today and wanted to take advantage of some vegan grub. I selected this place at random and am so happy that I did.   Great service. Pleasant atmosphere - on the student/hippy-ish/granola side of things - but that appeals to me.   Had a great order of vegan biscuits and gravy that reminded me of home (in the South), just a whole lot more vegan!  Yay!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States

dNO5-yd9LwyKZiwea6Vjhg.text: Fast tasty vegan coffee and dessert options, even for a non-Vegan. Enjoyed several visits there with my vegan wife during our trip to Phoenix. We'll be back next time we are in Phoenix

7ndzHHP_idIUoIfZovfnIw.text: I had the biscuits and gravy.  Was very yum and calmed my appetite.  Was very busy but the mood was polite and mellow.  Normal pricing but the food was not bland for vegan.   I will recommend.

N9Onl84_MGvjgmeqpDlxhw.text: Love Nami. The breakfast burritos are amazing. The ice cream cones are amazing. The people are amazing. Just a great place overall.

KSZv0g5tD8ryUo-qZTFHBA.text: Head next door to Green, Grub on some good food, then head back over here for dessert.  Tsoynamis are delicious. Do I ever get anything else? I def think about it... but no. Their deserts look tasty, but I can't say no to "ice cream".  Location inside is cute and clean. Parking sometimes is a pain, but worth it,

C3xl5kM1i2GkgHG-IzcFvw.text: Nami is super hip and cute when you walk in ans the store is very quaint and creative. They don't have too many gluten free options everyday but they have enough to definitely stop by. There ice cream is homemade and there are tons of options in that realm. I got the rocky road and the homemade marshmallows were creamy and tasted really fresh. The entire dessert was very refreshing. I usually don't like cheesecake but I tried the gluten free one and it was delicious. This place is definitely worth a try.

Fj8x4YfTfd6rO07yUult7w.text: I've been coming to this place and their sister shop Green for a few years now.   The tsoynami is just so darn good. I usually order vanilla soy with strawberries, graham crackers and marshmallow fluff mixed in. Perfect.  Their brunch on Sunday's is also great, aside from the long wait to order. But, I don't mind waiting for good food. One thing that did disappoint me last time I was there - I ordered a donut displayed in their case (along with other breakfast entrees for my group) and paid. While waiting for the food, they told me that they actually already sold the last of that donut. I really love donuts and it was one of the main reasons for my trip there so I was pretty bummed. They did have one other flavor left, maple. I settled for it and of course it was delicious so I wasn't too upset at that point... although I did have my heart set on the one I ordered and paid for.   You guys are great, only recommendation - make more donuts for Sunday mornings!

j3Jtexlb0PbZs3KAXhsZ4A.text: The s'mores ice cream is very good. Tasted like I was biting into a s'more. I really like their milk shakes too. I am pretty fond of anything coconut and most of their treats seem to be made with coconut milk. I live for this veg/vegan option #lactosintolerantlife

OHuCGBn7DQCKmYtuABD40Q.text: peanut butter cookie carrot cupcake vanilla cake banana donut  ...one of these things is not like the other...  Just kidding. Those are the four items I tried at Nami. Overall I was impressed and went home happy. The treats were moist and delightful to eat while chatting with company. I will be back for sure.   - carrot cupcake is a definite winner with it's slivers of carrots - banana donut takes second because of the real banana goodness it gave off and ! it was topped with nuts ! - peanut cookie was okay, but PEANUT flavor wasn't coming through as strong as I like - vanilla slice takes last place because even though it was decorated with icing and a small snicker doodle, there was no texture to the cake layers  The ratio of main ingredients in Nami's recipes was perfect so whoever does the baking has something good going on. Many vegan pastries I've tasted give off a distinctive after-taste of poor quality oils. Thankfully, I didn't taste that in Nami's goods.   On a side note, though, seriously - the icing is ridiculous. Too sweet and way too much!   One thing that would improve the store is better use of the counter space. Wouldn't it be nice for the owner to invest in a roomier display case?

ggLZVa4S9V6m12fdxNjLug.text: Went here for the first time last night after hearing all these great things about this place! I had the mash and better finger! Both were amazing and I was generally surprised that I enjoyed vegan ice cream! I would definitely recommend anybody looking for healthy ice cream and a great sweet snack to try this place out!

_phw9o-6DH65EAgpr3tkug.text: Returning to the Coronado neighborhood and have already made Nami our "couple times a week" stop! Whether for coffee, chai, pastries or vegan ice cream, it's a perfect little hipster joint for a break in your day that all your friends - whether paleo or vegan - will be perfectly happy at.   Simple 60s mod dining room, groovy eclectic music. The crowd is chill, with a steady influx coming & going regardless of the time of day. Blue haired college girls w/ their bearded boys, multi-generational families & LGBTQ couples -- everyone's seems at home here.   Check out Nami!

NEX-KXpZlYq2uR07Qfe4cg.text: I absolutely loved this little dessert shop!!!  It had the cutest atmosphere and so many choices. The staff was very friendly and i was little confused when it came to ordering, but they were very helpful. I came with my closed minded non vegan family and they thought the desserts wouldn't taste good, but they were proved wrong! The chocolate raspberry case was sosososo delicious. We also got a few tsoynamis. The betterfinger, a chocolate one, and the mash up. I really enjoyed the mash up. The texture with the added baked good made it very fun. I've never been too big of a fan of soy Ice creams, but I really enjoyed this one!  One thing that intrigued me that I didn't order was the orange juice with espresso. I've never even heard of anything of the sort end I definitely want to try it out sometime. I wish there was a location where I live in California!  I'm just going to make sure to stop by the next time I'm in Arizona :)

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Betterfinger tsoynami, chocolate tsoynami, the mash tsoynami, an apple fritter, and a slice of the raspberry chocolate cake

jD7lIg9ym1T-NNDOjwK0HA.text: I come here perhaps more often that I should. Tsoynamis are my downfall *queue up Price is Right fail horn*. But then again, its better than blubbering over to Dairy Queen and crying inside an M&M Blizzard of shame.  Inside this hopping hub inspired by the geniuses of Green is part bakery, part ice cream shop, and part coffe haus....sprinkled with brunch awesomeness in the morning and on weekends. This is my go-to spot for any sweet treat, because as my friends know I do not eat crap. I am now on primarily a low-calorie, low carb, primarily vegan/fish based diet. I watch what I eat and work out regularly.  How does Nami fit in? After a stressful day, instead of grabbing 5 beers and nachos, or a heaping 3 scoop fatty ice cream, I come here. I grab a 100% soy-based ice cream treat called a Tsoynami, which comes with dozens of variations made up by Nami. My personal favorite is The Doughboy, with vanilla soy soft serve and 100% organic chocolate chip cookie dough. Horrible for you? Meh, not great by any means. Better than Coldstone. Actually, you could probably have two Tsoynamis and be still way better off than anything Coldstone, Baskin Robbins, or Dairy Queen has to offer.   They also have a very high quality coffee bar which provides basic coffee fair, along with a dizzying arrangement of baked goods all vegan friendly. The vegan doughnuts blow my mind. I have yet to dance the doughnut dance at Nami, but I can do an eye test and say "I approve".  Overall, I can't give this place enough love. It's super trendy, the food on the weekends (look at their menu) are so to die for gang...its delicious. Green is a business genius for concocting the awesomeness that is Nami. They have this man happy, and a customer for life. Enjoy, 5 stars.... for everything they have here. Just go, if you haven't been yet. Just do it already!

photos.caption: Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. These huevos...are not your ordinary huevos
Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. Huevos rancheros Burrito  ;-)

y0aS-deWe3VWAPhAtAwEgQ.text: Bomb @$$ breakfast burritos. Been there 3 times now and never been disappointed. I even have meat eaters I've taken with me who will tell you its absolutely delicious.

v3e4D-D6oxKK5bGhKRvnGg.text: Worst customer service I've ever experienced. I ordered the dough boy swirl when I got my ice cream back it was a huge chocolate mess no vanilla what so ever. (Note I've been here multiple times and know what it should look like) I tried to eat it but it was just too much chocolate. I went back to let one of the girls there know with a dirty look on her face she quickly said no exchanges and turned her back to me right away. Literally no care in the world, not even I'm sorry let me try to make it better. So if you want to get something you didn't order don't bother letting the staff know because they don't care! Definitely wouldn't recommend this place.

ti-SGK_4uwlkQN2bFDOAcQ.text: So we wanted ice cream, and didn't think this visit would turn into an escapade. Ordered the the peach cobbler ice cream. My friend is deathly allergic to cashews. Little did we know the storemade granola contained cashews which is in the peach cobbler ice cream. When my friend noticed cashews were in her ice cream, she kindly asked the girl working the register if there were cashews, the girl said yes. She informed the cashier that she is severely allergic and to that the cashier said "oh well we have it posted" and pointed to a tiny sign in the kitchen. There was no reaction as to the well being of my friend. We looked over the menu again and there was absolutely no warning that there were nuts in the ice cream the only warning was that there may be cross contamination between all food products offered. Will not be visiting as the gals working were very rude and terrible.

bR7t0KUT6nUvSGh54uFnxg.text: Love everything about this place the ambiance, the staff, THE FOOD   come early on Sunday's, though, things go fast. I Really wanted chulaquiles and a spinach quiche Sunday, it was about 12 and they were out! Other than that, love it.

g1fuj-JnLu6eBZm-IW5TJg.text: This place is so yummy! Everything is fresh and has a lot of flavor! I'm in sweet heaven. Definitely place I'll be coming back to on my cheat days..

2pqPvnjSY_h2ee_JODXGhA.text: I always get excited for vegan breakfast places. This place exceeded all expectations! The biscuits and gravy is awesome! And it comes with tofu scramble and hash potatoes. Such a great place with a great vibe.

3222QDFQ3xPBNjOJ0JrQJQ.text: I liked their coffee, and they had a really really nice and clean bathroom, which I really appreciated after eggs benedict.

eqdb7wFjt5c3zJ1mg_jHuQ.text: Literally every time I come in here I know I will be treated to beautiful, gluten free-vegan orgasms in my mouth. Seriously, the food is that good. I have happily drooled thinking about the food at Green and the desserts at Nami and then hopped in my car and made the trek from Mesa to Phoenix on many occasions because it is just that good.

bW6FcGQLMiuDqh50dW_-6Q.text: Yummy-ness in a cup: tsoynami!! My first cup was the ginger snap with lemon...full to the brim and just the right blended texture. Perfect for these hot summer Phoenix days! Then I had a second try because I was craving it this weekend...the Almond Oy vey! Not made as well as it was last week. Photo of Nami - Phoenix, AZ, United States. My first tsoynami with friends :)

3DMnYcb8QVGd1UDXYNvGEQ.text: Come for breakfast, but come back for the desserts.  A co-worker of mine and her husband are steadfast vegetarians and fell in love with this place almost as fast as they fell in love with Green next door.  This place is owned and run by the same owners as Green, and the space is small just like its counterpart.  Whereas Green is more of a lunch and dinner spot, Nami is more of a breakfast/dessert spot.  We got here around 10am on a Saturday morning and by the time we sat down, it was packed.  Not surprising given how many vegans and vegetarians live around Downtown.  My co-worker recommended I get the biscuits and gravy.  I saw a couple of cupcakes that caught my eye in the pastry case (cookie dough cupcake and red velvet cupcake) so I got those and an OJ too.  As with Green, you order at the counter and seat yourselves.  Total for all of my food was $20.  Food came out to us in less than 10 minutes.  Let me first go into the cupcakes.  I've had vegan cupcakes before at Treehouse Bakery just west of here, and these were equally delicious.  The frosting on both was dense, but creamy and decadent.  The cake itself was actually more dense than Treehouse's which made eating two pretty tough, but it was worth it.  As for the biscuits and gravy, I actually loved the tofu eggs as they put enough spice and herbs on those to make me forget I was eating tofu.  It didn't have the texture of an egg at all, but it was still great.  The home fries were also tasty and crispy and light.  As for the biscuits and gravy itself, mixed reactions on this one.  There was a lot of onion on my gravy which seemed to be a little bit of overkill.  The biscuits were also a little dry.  It was okay, but I think Bragg's Diner (also just west of here) does the vegan biscuits and gravy thing a little better.  All in all though, I was pleased with my first trip here.  The vibe is super relaxed, the gals behind the counter are super friendly, and the portions of food on every dish I saw were plenty hearty.  Even though the food is all vegan, I can assure you that no one leaves here hungry.  I can't totally recommend the biscuits and gravy for breakfast, but I fully intend to explore other breakfast menu items in the future.  I've also heard a lot of good things about the tsoynamis, so that'll be on my to do list.  Just be warned, once you take one look at that pastry display case, its pretty much impossible not to order one.

Roih4X07quVmAEvPdLJdtA.text: I love Nami's "Cactus Haboob" latte, which has a yummy cinnamon agave flavoring that is perfect for my taste buds.  I also like the turkey melts, breakfast burritos, and huckleberry pancakes here.  The prices are pretty reasonable, the cafe itself is really cute, and the staff are very sweet.

MgnHIRCuKUfl0LZVekJ-jg.text: This is now my new go-to when visiting Phoenix. Everything is soooo good! My first time here I had the wing ding dang burrito. It was a little spicy but that's how I like my food! The tofu scramble was tasty as well. Although it was breakfast time, I also had the Cookie Monster tsoynami. Being vegan, I don't get to have a whole lot of sweet treats at restaurants, but the tsoynami was life changing. Their McBagel is also very tasty! I am so glad my friends told me about this place.

E3xuv6h6rE6BH2gnT4QIZg.text: Nami makes incredible food and sweets! I am originally from the Bay Area and I will be so sad to move back after school simply because there is no Nami back home. They're my go to place for vegan breakfast/brunch and I would recommend them to EVERYONE

GLs2GQFVgNkmdDWBuIJL0w.text: Poor customer service and terrible parking! They were "out" of items on the menu that they should have! If you're there for pickup, they want you to stand in the long line of people ordering to pick up your food that you already ordered. So inconvenient. They didn't even have the food ready when I got there. They had to prepare it which took 15 mins. When they called me, they didn't have the other stuff I preordered ready either. They didn't even apologize. They made me get back in line and order them. So unprofessional and frustrating! The cashier Amy and the other workers were rude too!

5HV9qK-s1PCLZ3MfQpLmVA.text: Okay, so I've made a Yelp account just to leave this review. I've been vegan for years and naturally have been coming here since nami and green have been open!!! I've always loved Sunday brunch and would come almost every weekend. The baristas were ALWAYS sweet and friendly no matter the weather or the length of the line (usually out the door and wrapped around everywhere) and would even go out of their way to remember my name. Around 6-9 months ago that attitude changed. All the new hires are rude and unhelpful and the atmosphere of the place, consequentially, turned clique-y and unwelcoming. Today I placed an order for pick-up because I had to go straight from nami to work and when I went up to the counter the cashier told me, "You're gonna have to wait in the line like everyone else." Woah. I didn't know the meaning of "pick-up" had changed and even then you didn't need to be a dickhead about it... I obviously didn't know. I've noticed the lines becoming shorter as well with this weekend as an exception. So I was forced to wait in line for 35 minutes for food that was sitting there for 20 minutes prior to me coming to pick it up. Today's service was above-and-beyond terrible. Yes, it's hot. Yes, lines were long. But that is no excuse to be a bitch. I work in food service too and if I had said anything like that to a customer, my ass would've been fired. I haven't even eaten my food because by the time I got through the line, it was cold. It's a shame because I've been putting off writing this review because the food is so. damn. good. But nami and green are places that vegans, vegetarians, and omnivores alike come to eat and honestly the image that these girls are portraying of vegans hurts all of us and makes us ALL seem like pretentious bitches. Again, this review has been a long time in the making but today was just the last straw. Do no harm but take no shit.  P.S. that girl with the nicotine patch needs to be fired.

hejG3esbBfGDDtCanJ1l-Q.text: The food is delicious but it's seriously overpriced. The people who work there are nice but the decor is minimal. I really hate that vegan/vegetarian food is always crazy expensive. I liked this place but it's not nice enough to go here for a special occasion, so I probably won't be back.

KhDFqInAVrTiDNt7Kef_KQ.text: My husband and I had lunch at Green at some point during Thanksgiving week, which is next door to Nami. We had such a terrible experience at Green, that we were hesitant to go over to Nami (I believe they're owned by the same people). Read through Nami's reviews, and decided to take the plunge anyway.  No regrets at all! It was such a relief, the two ladies working that day were so nice and accommodating. They took the time to explain their tSoynami menu to us, and they didn't rush us. I ordered the Chai tSoynami, and I believe my husband got the cookies and cream one. We loved it! Portions are huge, but we licked up every last bit.   I knocked of a star because they are pretty vague about what they put in their tSoynami's. Some of the items seemed too good to be True. Would be nice if they listed detailed ingredients on their menu, since a lot of commercialized "vegan" foods tend to be highly processed and, sadly, unhealthier versions of what they imitate.   Anyhow, we were visiting from LA, and I really wanted to stop by again before we left but we never got to! So sad! Anyway, we're excited to go back next Thanksgiving!   Thanks Nami !

IxzNoWMabJwOUsyy5vJoog.text: This bakery was delicious!! I wish they had an east valley location! They have amazing food for health-conscious folks like me.

XrVQba9trINZD3rPA94lRA.text: This place is amazing. I wish I heard of it sooner. Perfect place to satisfy a sweet tooth while staying healthy! Only reason I gave 4stars is because they were out of doughnuts which I am eager to go back and try

bQgbBjEEurBUN1TRj85WJQ.text: A family favorite. Will continue to go back. The staff is always very generous and helpful. The food is fantastic. You would never know this is a vegan restaurant. I bring non-veg family here all the time and they always enjoy it and ask to meet there again. Absolutely lovely!

K2m8bTbXjGuZhOOsXiTffg.text: A sweet hub of delicious treats. I love my non dairy swirl! The people who work here are sweet too!!

YAFuKKAt8FYIO0w-Vx4BPg.text: This place is amazing!  Best Vegan spot in Phoenix.  My wife and I have driven from north Phoenix every weekend, totally worth the drive.  Friendly employees, great atmosphere and awesome food!

yZJwfDdU1FkUVeUfpq4zWA.text: AHHH...mazing! Affordable, delicious, and generous portions! My daughter is severely lactose intolerant so we are always on the search for diary free dessert places. We found it with Nami! We will definitely be coming back!

d1Bs_KaYGob7Vozmtbm4aQ.text: Delish espresso drinks, yummy cupcakes, and soy soft serve so good it passes for real soft serve with the pickiest critic - my 4 year old daughter!  Here's the deal - I used to be vegan YEARS ago so I am perhaps more open to places that specialize in vegetarian/vegan.  However, I don't SEEK out vege places anymore because now I am back to eating everything (see my review on the Pork Dip from St. Francis if you're skeptical).  I decided to check this place out because they have a modern vibe to it and all they do is coffee and desserts. I've passed it every Saturday for the past year and have always been drawn in by their clever signage. I had NO idea they were an "alternative" cafe until I walked in and checked the menu.   This place has incredible baked goods and they do a great job with the coffee. That's pretty much all I need to be happy :) For starters, it's hard to find a good espresso spot in Phoenix. Secondly, I remember that with the vegan-restricted diet my general rule of thumb was if I was eating out and the food tasted good - it was probably not vegan. This place has just perfected sweet treats that are gluten and dairy free which just makes me even more impressed with it.   This is definitely getting bookmarked as my cafe/bakery go-to when I'm in central Phoenix.

YLUUd3kbDdtUn_HgZAfeCw.text: I usually don't review something food related unless i have gone to it at least 3 times but with this place i was just so disappointed my second real time in, I don't think I want to come here again. The first time i went here was a random Sunday with my girlfriend and we were looking for places to eat and everything was closed but we say this place had donuts and i was really feeling like having one. Got 2 one for me, one for her and they were really good and would recommend them. The second time we came in for brunch a little before 1 on a Sunday found out they were out of 3 different things on the menu so my girlfriend got the "Wing" Ding Dang and I got the French Toast. So we sat down and someone came over to tell me that they're out of the French toast (So 4 different things) and i looked over the menu and I didn't want anything else so i ask just to have a refund. So i have to go back over to the register and there was a line and I don't like to cut so i just waited in line...again. If my girlfriend brings me here again i hope they don't run out of everything and i can actually try something and give this place a good review.

eLVqo0oHE47Z21xSIQh_yg.text: Their banana tsoynami is amazing.  Seriously, I'm not 100% sure if there is crack in the banana tsoynami (is crack vegan?) but it's that addictive!    It's a little bit pricey, but who cares?!?  Yum!!

YbvbMDj3gd07cvInVks2mA.text: Even if you don't have dietary restrictions, Nami is worth a try. It's a cute, small shop located right next to Green. They share the same parking lot. Parking can be a bit tough, so try going on an off time.  I had a chocolate chip cookie, which was pretty good - a little dry, but the flavor was there. They have some food items and soy ice cream, as well as coffee drinks. I'd go back to satisfy my sweet tooth after a meal at Green.

XlGBfQWiUhb_wpw9CjL6dA.text: NOTHING LIKE THIS PLACE ANYWHERE!!! i always have to get a different tsoynami when i come to phoenix. i crave this year round and look forward to coming back to phoenix almost solely to visit nami. it is soooooooooo delicious. this time i had a betterfinger tsoynami with chick-o-sticks in it. to die for. amazing.

Oo9NEgCuSNKsu09T8hfIDA.text: I don't even know how many times I've been to Nami since it opened. It really doesn't matter that it's 30 minutes away from my house... I make up reasons to go weekly.  An update on the "Here's what we ordered" section: 1. Cinnamon roll - A classic. They heat it up for you so that it's too warm and fragrant and irresistible not to finish. It's perfect. I hate it. I hate them. (That's a lie.) 2. Chocolate cake doughnut -  Call me a conspiracy theorist, but I'm pretty sure that this is just a ring-shaped piece of chocolate cake. That said, it's a very good piece of ring-shaped chocolate cake. 3. Sugar cookie -  I brought this home for my very non-vegan little sister, who tasted it immediately and said, "This (nom) is the best (nom) sugar cookie (nom) I've ever had in my life!" 4. House made granola, yogurt & berry parfait -  Nami's granola is like cocaine. You will never be able to have enough of it. But that's okay, because on some mornings it just feels right. I do wish the yogurt wasn't soy-based and the berries weren't frozen, but honestly, it still rocks. 5. Vegan Victory Bar -  If you're looking for something more wholesome, this peanut butter-chocolate-spirulina (hence the green color)-nut-seed bar will satisfy your sweet tooth without making you feel gypped for picking the 'healthier' option. 6. Hazelnut milk latte -  Any of the lattes from Nami are fantastic. Choose coconut, almond, soy, hazelnut, or rice milk for a strong, nutty cup of awesome (and you can sweeten it with Stevia!) 7. The MASH - If you're feeling daring, this is a fun way to spin the wheel of dessert fortune. I've ended up with a carrot cake tsoynami and a mint chocolate chip one. Both were delicious, but nothing beats the Monsoon. 8. Brownie - Literally the best brownie I've ever had. So chewy-rich-intensely-chocolate-y. It didn't even taste like there was flour in it. I want a hundred of them. Right now. 9. Peanut butter bar - Don't be intimidated by this dense looking log. It's actually a light, crunchy, nougat-y bar with a thin layer of chocolate on top, although it does resemble peanut butter fudge.  The thing is... I've never had brunch here, which means I should probably head back on Sunday to get a feel for it. Now there's an idea.

9D3hxD8LJo9kh90p_GuRNg.text: Yum! Just finished off the Rocky Road tSoynami with pretzels instead of chocolate chips. It was magical. The pretzels remained crunchy till the very last bite.. Very exciting.  I love that the base is VEGAN and ORGANIC. Eating 16 ounces of ice cream never made me so happy!!!!

uxcQuDUjNFZmdtKHN4gkqA.text: This is my new favorite spot! I can't have dairy and all other vegan ice creams I have had have been subpar, but this place is amazing!! I get the chunky monkey tsoynami  (banana and chocolate) with marshmallow fluff and even though I'm ridiculously picky, the staff are always so patient and accommodating! The last couple times I went I had the pleasure of Marissa helping me and she is just as sweet as the treats  I strongly recommend this place to everyone, vegan or not!

GUeSCsXEDqxHJqeYi5hmqg.text: I have a dairy allergy and a weakness for Ice Cream. I tried one of Nami's tSoynami's ($4.50 for a lot) which is sort of like a DQ Blizzard only made with what tastes like Homemade Ice Cream only this has Soy rather than Cow milk. I went with the Fluffernutterin (organic peanut butter, banana, ricemellow fluff and toasted marshmallow flavor). I can honestly say this was better than a DQ Blizzard. They also have yummy cupcakes and cookies and other treats, coffee & Sunday Brunch. I also like their restaurant Green located next door and I am far from a Vegetarian but good is good.

M0dIWg4whzO_IyJiwipsUQ.text: when you're gluten-free, vegan, soy milk and almond milk intolerant and you can't have any caffeine, it's torture to go into any bakery or coffeehouse.  Not at Nami.  What was great about this place was the gluten-free vegan treats...yes they are sugary...my favorite is the two snickerdoodle cookies pressed together with some sort of awesome creamy goodness in the middle.  And, they can make steamers with rice or coconut milk!!!  finally a coffeehouse I feel good going to!

vNzd5bal_0bwd5BL2k12mA.text: How can you not like Nami? Delicious pastries, brunch, coffee, and killer service. Need I say more? I visit this place often and I love their yogurt parfait! Please go. Enjoy some sweets paired with a hot cup of coffee and take all your friends there.

ZCGHuP3w5BBCWSp2cFTF3Q.text: I was introduced by a friend and got a "banana cream pie"! in love forever! I also love the red velvet cupcake! (when its in stock). Service there is usually always nice and prompt, this evening the girl working wasn't as friendly as I am used to the other girls working there but that isn't going to make me rate less because I am addicted, muhahahahha!

ohLfZxztZMAoHQL26P4A2w.text: I had only tried this place once but I plan to go back. The place is small but I like the decor.  The lady who helped me was nice. The tSoynami was amazing! I didn't think it was going to be that tasty but it was. Give it a try!

xPkJXj1EDqcF3jlnUyFB1g.text: Last Friday, a friend and I were at the baseball game when she recommended trying Nami, even saying I would like it better than my favorite ice cream place. We looked up the hours and left the game early. We booked it down to Nami before closing, arriving right at 9:30. We were told they had to close the drawer and could only serve the two parties in front of us but could not serve us. I was flabbergasted that a company would have such a lack of customer service and refuse our business. I was so excited to try this place but will not be going back because of how we were treated. I will be sure to share my experience at Nami with others.

0U12osRbnVpayJ5TBJA7Ag.text: The tsoynami's here are delicious. I had the almond oy-vay: coconut, chocolate syrup and almonds. My friend made her own with peanut butter, coconut and chocolate cookies.  Both were really good and pretty large for $4.50. We also tried the chocolate baked donut and the granola. The donut was okay, the granola had lots of cashews and cinnamon and was really tasty. Definitely the highlight was the tsoynamis i wouldnt come back for the test. Yeah the people working there could be friendlier but it wont stop me from coming back.

As3F5QtvFLfoh6yHLorYgA.text: yaaayyyy!!!! A completely dairy-free dessert zone!!! EVERYTHING here is vegan, even the insanely delicious truffles! (I had rocky road....I almost melted and went to chocolate heaven right there!)   The Tsoynami's are outrageous! I haven't had 'soft serve ice cream' in a looooooong time...(figured out I was allergic to dairy like 8 years ago..it's been a while!) ...I had coffee coco loco, mmmmm......(writing this review is going to make me leave out the door right now for some more....)...My family ordered the clunky monkey and LOVED it (they are all dairy eaters, so, I think that says a lot!)    I can't wait to go back and try some cupcakes, and get me some more of those truffles.....SO GLAD there is another location near me!!! (or AM I???)

443qibguq3eENWBUp9gaZg.text: The ice cream was good but not at all creamy.

gYGhZ68jIwvSZEoj4jKaMQ.text: I decided to try this place while I was visiting Phoenix since all the Yelp reviews gave them 5 stars! I can see why!!!! I had asked the cashier to recommend me a flavor for their T'soynami, as I have never heard of anything like this before. She suggested the vegan nami. pXmZGP0nnmu2ChlHi00YDA.text: Stopped by to try the tsoynamis and it was great until I got half way through and found a small hair in it! Grossed me out!!!

77yQsjRjONtuZFOgToPQpA.text: Reviewing the coffee bar half of the Nami theme only...  Nami has been the closest espresso bar to my home since opening late last year.  Seeing as the coffee bean is a central part of my daily existence, it took me long enough to make my first visit.  Unfortunately, I would have been fine just delaying it indefinitely.  I can appreciate the whole vegan thing if that's their deal - there's a niche market for that and somebody's got to fill it.  What is astonishing is the refusal to placate the non-vegan crowd (i.e. overwhelming majority) and carry some half & half.   Introducing almond milk to whatever you're drink may be is an utter waste of espresso - trust me on this one.  The novelty of the concept, the trendy and energetic vibe, and the friendly baristas are among Nami's merits.  It's not the kind of coffee house that beckons you to sit down with a laptop or a book while you sip your favorite hot drink.  Hard, uncomfortable seats encourage you get what you came for and take it for the road.

5Tvm5OPR0MgEaheOnmIBtA.text: Frittersssss are seriously addicting. We get coffee here almost every morning....and fritters every. morning. too...... staff is fun and friendly. Different artist work on the walls each month. Brunch! On Sunday's they have a special. Oh and can't forgets the vegan donuts and all the rest of the yummy desserts like Tsoynami! (Vegan ice cream)

Y5ZoxdtGGW3JMs8soThk2A.text: The first time I went here, I didn't come away feeling very satisfied mostly because I'm cheap at times. I spent nearly $7 on a cookie and a "winkie." The winkie was good but it wasn't *that* good. I was sorta sulking about that and didn't think I'd go back. But alas, on my next visit, I got one of their Dairy-Queen-like "Tsoynamis" and damn if that stuff isn't crack. I went back a second time in four days because I had to have some of that cream, non-dairy goodness. I had a PB-Chocolate one and more recently a 'Smores one with marshmallow fluffer. Good stuff. I like the coconut milk better in some ways. Anyway, I have to be careful around that place but I mean that in a good way.

15Pug-9tyUUlqzVVINvoGw.text: Nami has great donuts. They are like a cross between the cake donut and the more airy donut. They are chewy and more substantial than the airy-type donuts. The donuts are really delicious. The tsoynamis are always good. Their grits are cheesy (vegan cheesy) and come with half a roasted jalapeno on the top, so you can cut it up and spice up the dish, but the grits are one of the best things on the menu. I've always loved their spicy wings. I feel like they are still getting their feet wet on some other items, and hope they improve over time. The scramble, for instance, is somewhat dry and flavorless. The hash potatoes, which are usually a favorite of mine, are also somewhat dry and flavorless. If they could improve on those two things, I think it would be much better. They usually have a special each weekend. Get there right when they open if you want a big donut selection. The place is packed on Sundays!

BF6tQarqp_M0o4Ns13jn-g.text: I am not a dessert person by any means but in the 100+ degree Phoenix heat I love a cold Soynami.
